s, but are easily bowled over by direct attacks. You aren'tgiving yourself the chance to exploit this weakness in the Catalan. Insteadyou are planning a rook invasion on c7 in 10 moves' time. --- It is, of course,a question of style and what you are looking for from the opening. If you wanta safe game with few losing chances and a small plus, then the Catalan is foryou. If you like grinding out wins in rook and pawn endgames it will suit youfine. --- Despite the rather gloomy prognosis for Black above, I have examinedsome interesting counter measures for him. Almost all of the world elite areprepared to defend against the Catalan and have introduced many weaponsagainst it. --- This book aims to cover all the important ideas in everyvariation of the Catalan. Inevitably there will be gaps as it is such a wide,strategically complex and ever developing opening. I can only apologise inadvance for any omissions.} (4. -- {Neil McDonald, Gravesend, April 2017}) *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Move Orders & Transpositions"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2017.08.07"]{I would recommend you look at some of the games in this book and get a feelfor the Catalan before reading this section. It will help you decide what moveorder might be right for you.} 1. -- ({In this book I have used} 1. d4 {A very common alternative path is} Nf6 (1... d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {as White and Black's standard way to reach the Catalan, but there are variousother routes. Sometimes, but not always, I have changed the move order of theactual game for the sake of clarity.} (4. --)) 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 {.}) ({More subtle is Kramnik's move order versus Nakamura in Chapter Seven:} 1. Nf3Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. c4 O-O ({in this sequence you'd also haveto prepare for moves such as} 5... d4) 6. d4 dxc4 {. Notice the former worldchampion's shrewd way of getting to the Catalan Mainline. By delaying d2-d4 hehas cut out any 'nonsense' with ...Bb4+ (Chapter Four) or ...Nc6 (Chapter Five), or an early ...dxc4 and ...Bd7 intending ...Bc6 (as in Chapter Six). Blackhas also never been given the chance to grab the pawn on c4 and try to hold onto it (Chapter Three). Hence it saves a lot of learning of sidelines if youplay like this. In the Nakamura game White then went} 7. Ne5 {,} ({avoidingthe whole of the} 7. Qc2 {mainline.})) ({After} 1. Nf3 {,} {By starting 1 Nf3,you give yourself the option after} Nf6 {of continuing, say,} ({you need to beready for} 1... c5 {– a natural choice would be} 2. c4 {, making it aSymmetrical English} ({or} 2. g3 {.}) ({Or maybe you could change style toconfound an opponent who doesn't play the Sicilian as Black with} 2. e4 {!})) ({Here is another tweak in move order which might have a practical value, takenfrom Giri-Grischuk in Chapter One:} 1... d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 ({note that inthis move order you might also face the Queen's Gambit Accepted with} 3... dxc4{and then, say,} 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5) 4. g3 {. Giri delays putting a pawn ond4 until Black has committed himself to 1...d5. This is useful if you likeplaying the Catalan, but don't want to risk 1 d4 in case Black plays theKing's Indian or Grünfeld, or some other set-up involving ...g7-g6. Maybe youare also keen to avoid mainline Queen's Indian-style set-ups where Black hasplayed ...e7-e6, but avoided ...d7-d5.}) 2. c4 {and then, after} g6 {, withmoves like} ({or} 2... e6) 3. g3 {, 4 Bg2, 5 Nc3 and 6 0-0, etc, all the timeavoiding/delaying d2-d4 to keep it as an English.}) ({Move order is especiallyimportant in Chapter Two where White chooses to regain his pawn after ...d5xc4with the immediate Qa4+ and Qxc4. In that case White does best to delay eitherd2-d4 or Nf3 in order to have time to keep Black bottled up on the queenside.For example, as in Artemiev-Safarli with} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Qxc4 a6 {and now having delayed d2-d4, White has time toplay} 7. Qc2 $1 {. This gets the queen out of the way of} b5 {which would wintime for Black to equalize with ...Bb7.}) ({Alternatively, GrandmasterTkachiev, who is an expert on this line, has adopted a move order which delaysNf3:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 {You'll have to keep your eyes openas there are many quirks of move order and unexpected transpositions in theCatalan. Notably in Chapter One} Bb4+ (4... dxc4 5. Qa4+ {. If now} Nbd7 6.Qxc4 a6 {then} 7. Qc2 $1 {is the same anti-b7-b5 recipe.} (7. --)) 5. Bd2 Be7 {could well transpose to 4...Be7 if White subsequently plays Bf4: in the formercase White has spent two moves getting his bishop to f4, but Black has alsospent two moves getting his bishop to e7, so tempo-wise it is quits. Butremember if you look at some games with this line in a book or in a databaseyou might have the same position, but the games might have different movenumbers}) *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "1: The Closed Centre"][Black "?"][Result "*"][ECO "E01"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "8"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2017.08.07"]{In this chapter we'll look at lines in which Black maintains a pawn on d5.The typical sequence is} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {, when Blackchooses between:} -- ({the immediate} 4... Be7) ({and} 4... Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 {. Black plays in a straightforward, classical way against the Catalan. Hedevelops his kingside pieces, prepares to castle his king into safety, and ifnecessary is ready to bolster his strong-point on d5 by creating a triangle ofpawns in the centre with ...c7-c6. --- Nonetheless with correct play White isable to exert steady pressure. A key aim is to increase the scope of theCatalan bishop with the pawn advance e2-e4. Black has to be careful not tofall into a passive position. --- We'll begin by examining 4...Be7 and thenmove on to the more 'modern' 4...Bb4+. After that we'll return again to 4...Be7 to look at two other approaches by White.}) *[Event "1: Basel"][Site "?"][Date "2016.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Naiditsch, A."][Black "Kopylov, M."][Result "1-0"][ECO "A14"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "45"][EventDate "2016.??.??"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2017.08.07"]1. d4 {The Catalan can be reached through various move orders.} ({A typicalalternative is} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 {.}) ({The present gameactually begun} 1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. d4 c6 {, but as in most cases in this book I have standardized the move order to makethings clearer.}) 1... d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 ({Here, for example, White couldalso fianchetto at once with} 3. g3 {.}) 3... Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan differsfrom the Queen's Gambit in that the bishop is developed to g2.} Be7 {Many topplayers are happy to defend Black's position after this modest move.} ({Nonetheless, on the whole modern theory suggests that if Black intends thisset-up he might have done well to insert the moves} 4... Bb4+ 5. Bd2 {and onlythen play} Be7 {. --- EXERCISE: Before reading on, can you work out why? ---ANSWER: Assuming Black keeps a pawn on d5 (rather than plays a system with ...d5xc4), the consensus is that he is being slightly generous to his opponent.He allows him to arrange a rapid Nbd2 and e2-e4 when the plan could have beenat least delayed by the interpolation 4...Bb4+ 5 Bd2 Be7. This is because ond2 the white bishop blocks the square that the knight needs to support e2-e4.})({Note too that the immediate} 4... c5 {to strike at White's centre isexamined in Chapter Five (this is a Queen's Gambit Tarrasch, but we need to beready for it if we play the Catalan).}) 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({Later in thechapter we'll look at games where White defends the c4-pawn either with} 6.Nbd2) ({or} 6. Qc2 {.}) 6... c6 {Black has achieved a lot after only six moves.His king is safe and he has a solid centre with no weaknesses.} ({In contrast,after} 6... b6 {hanging pawns can be inflicted on Black immediately with} 7.cxd5 {. Play could continue} exd5 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. Ne5 Na6 10. Bf4 c5 11. Rc1 {with a strong build up of white pieces in the centre. It's no surprise thatBlack has poor results in this line.}) 7. Qc2 {QUESTION: Is this a strong andsensible move? --- ANSWER: Yes! On c2 the white queen defends the c4-pawn,ruling out any pawn snatch with ...d5xc4 followed by ...b7-b5 clinging on tothe material. Also thinking about the c-file, in this type of structureBlack's so-called freeing move is ...c7-c5. If he can carry out this pawnbreak without incurring any immediate disadvantage he has good chances toequalize. The queen's presence on c2 deters the advance. Speaking moregenerally, the white queen vacates the d1-square for a rook, probably the oneon f1, to support the d4-pawn. And, finally, she also aims at the e4-square insupport of White's plan which is discussed below.} b6 {With this reply Blackcontinues his logical scheme of development: his queen's bishop will go to b7,then the knight on b8 will be developed to d7 (jumping ahead I should say thislooks like a mistake – see the note to Black's 9th, below), and the rook froma8 will be shifted to c8. Finally he will be ready to strike out with theaforementioned ...c7-c5, which will be all the more effective in view of thewhite queen's somewhat exposed position on c2.} 8. Nbd2 $1 {One of thetrademarks of the Catalan is that White avoids a quick development of hisqueen's knight. He waits to see what is the best square for it. In thisexample Naiditsch plans to use the horse to support the pawn advance e2-e4,but doesn't want to allow ...d5xc4 without the chance to recapture. Thereforehe puts the knight on d2 rather than c3, which would interfere with hisqueen's defence of the c4-pawn. --- We shall see that in certain variationsWhite chooses to play Nc3 rather than Nbd2. However, these tend to be lesspopular, more speculative tries for advantage. Or perhaps White was denied thechance to be flexible as he chose c3 for the knight before he knew for sure itwas going to be a Catalan. --- A delayed development of the queen's knight,which probably goes to d2 in the end, is far more characteristic of theCatalan.} Bb7 9. e4 {QUESTION: I'm still slightly confused why 4...Bb4+ 5 Bd2Be7 is recommended instead as the correct procedure for Black. After all, he'gifts' White the developing move Bd2. How big a difference would it make tothe game – a slight or big change? --- ANSWER: We can debate whether thewhite bishop is better on d2 than c1 – White might find a way to justify itsplacing on d2, or find a use for the vacated c1-square. However, the mainpoint is that White's smooth build-up with Nbd2 and e2-e4 would have beenobstructed because his knight is denied the d2-square. This seems tosignificantly outweigh any benefits for White in having shifted his bishop tod2 'for free'. --- As a rule, if White can achieve the e2-e4 advance beforeBlack can respond ...d5xc4 and ...c7-c5 in a safe way he will have a good game.--- EXERCISE: What do you now think is the best move for Black out of thefollowing choice: 9...dxe4, 9...Na6 and 9...Nbd7 - ?} Nbd7 $6 {The game move 9...Nbd7 proves one routine move too many.} ({ANSWER: Here} 9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 {Instead, Black could play a solid move like} Nbd7 {, hoping to get in ...c6-c5in the future, but White could build up with} (10... c5 $2 {falls for a trapthat you should always be looking out for if Black has an undefended bishop onb7:} 11. Nxf6+ $1 Bxf6 ({or equally} 11... gxf6 12. Ng5 $1) 12. Ng5 $1 {uncovering an attack on b7 whilst threatening mate on h7. Black loses theexchange after} Bxg5 13. Bxb7 {.}) 11. Rd1 {, exerting indirect pressure alongthe d-file. Then} c5 $2 {, still fails:} ({of course, Black could playpassively with say} 11... Rc8 {, but he remains uncomfortable after} 12. Bf4 {, etc}) 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 ({the black queen hangs after} 12... Nxf6 13. dxc5) 13.Ng5 $1 {(our familiar trick)} Bxg5 14. Bxb7 Rb8 15. dxc5 $1 Rxb7 16. c6 Rc7 17.Rxd7 Rxd7 18. Bxg5 Qxg5 19. cxd7 {and White has emerged with an extra pawn onthe seventh rank. A long variation, but it flows naturally.}) ({More dynamicwas} 9... Na6 $1 {.} {Perhaps it is best for White to answer 9...Na6 with theimmediate} 10. a3 $1 {, hoping to get in 11 e5 Nd7 12 cxd5 cxd5. Then} ({Then after} 10. e5 Nd7 {note the knight is pleased that the d7-square isavailable to it,} ({whereas in the game it is forced to the back rank after} 10... Ne8) 11. cxd5 $2 {, which proves highly effective in the game after therecapture} ({instead (after 9...Na6 10 e5 Nd7), White could try} 11. a3 $5 {to deny the black knight the b4-square, but this seems a little late as} c5 $1{then undermines the white centre and gives Black the chance to answer c4xd5with ...Bxd5, activating his bishop}) 11... cxd5 {,} ({Black has thezwischenzug} 11... Nb4 $1 {to get the knight to the excellent d5-square after}12. Qb3 Nxd5 {. Then} 13. Ne4 c5 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Nxc5 Bxc5 {would transposeto the game Phillips-Kovalyov given later in the chapter. This was anexcellent win by Black.})) 10... c5 $1 {is still effective for Black, thoughmaybe not as good as the similar strike at White's centre with 11...c5 above.--- These moves have been the subject of high-level games. For example, H.Nakamura-Yu Yangyi, Gibraltar 2017, went} 11. exd5 exd5 12. Rd1 Rc8 13. dxc5Nxc5 14. b4 Ne6 15. Bb2 dxc4 16. Nxc4 Qc7 17. Rac1 Qb8 18. Qe2 Qa8 {and now}19. Ne3 {with 20 Nf5 in mind might be a small plus to White.}) 10. e5 {Thanksto Black's passive ninth move, White is able to establish a stable wedge inthe centre whilst keeping Black's bishop on b7 shut in.} Ne8 11. cxd5 cxd5 {The black knights are deprived of the f6-square, making the idea of a directkingside assault attractive to White.} 12. Re1 {White's so-called mysteriousrook move had two purposes. Firstly, the rook deters any challenge to White'spawn dominance in the centre with ...f7-f6 by putting indirect pressure on e6.And, secondly, it vacates the f1-square for the knight on d2, allowing Whiteto build up pressure on the kingside and restrain Black's activity along thec-file.} Qc8 $2 {Naturally Black would love to exchange queens to escape thedanger of an attack on his king, but this and his next move prove an utterwaste of time.} ({He should play} 12... Rc8 13. Qd1 Qc7 14. Nf1 Qc2 15. Qxc2Rxc2 16. Ne3 Rc8 17. Bd2 {is some advantage to White in the endgame as theblack pieces are cramped, but at least Black has avoided a direct kingsideattack.}) 13. Qd1 {The queen doesn't mind being pushed back home as the spaceadvantage on e5 is permanent. Besides if the knight on f3 moves out of the wayshe has a direct route into attack on the kingside via the g4- or h5-squares.}Qc6 14. Nf1 Rc8 {EXERCISE: What move thwarts Black's plans and adds vigour toWhite's own? --- ANSWER:} 15. Ne3 $1 {The knight not only prevents 15...Qc2,forcing the unwelcome exchange of queens after all, but also prepares tocharge to g4 to lead a kingside assault. --- It's obvious Black lost a tempowith ...Qc8, ...Qc6 and ...Rc8 when he could have gone ...Rc8 and ...Qc7 intwo moves, In that case White's knight wouldn't have been in time getting toe3 to stop Qc2.} b5 16. h4 {A move in the style of the King's Indian Attack.White's h-pawn could be used as a battering ram to break up the black kingsidewith h5-h6, or remain on h4 and support the attacking move Ng5.} Nb6 {QUESTION:It seems Black is ready to eliminate White's knight with 17...Nc4 and 18...Nxe3, when the idea of ...Qc2 reappears. What measures should White takeagainst this?} 17. b3 $1 {ANSWER: After this simple precautionary move Black'squeenside counterplay is hamstrung.} b4 18. Bd2 Nc7 19. Rc1 Qd7 20. Ng5 {White is justified in starting an attack against the black king with potentialsacrifices as Naiditsch is rewarded for his careful strategic play. Black isdeprived of activity, which means he has a queen, three minor pieces and arook sitting on the left side of the board, cut off from going to the aid oftheir king by the blocked centre, and unable to distract the white pieces fromgoing all in against the underdefended black king.} Ba6 21. Ng4 Nb5 {QUESTION:can you see White's winning move?} ({The last chance was} 21... Bd3 {to atleast get a bishop involved in the king's defence.}) 22. Nf6+ $1 {ANSWER!} gxf623. exf6 ({Black's king will be mated in short order after} 23. exf6 Bxf6 24.Qh5 {More resistant is} h6 (24... Bxg5 25. Qxg5+ Kh8 26. Qf6+ Kg8 27. Bh6 {and 28 Qg7 mate follows;} (27. --)) ({or} 24... Rfd8 25. Qxh7+ Kf8 26. Bxb4+Ke8 27. Qg8# {.}) 25. Qxh6 Bxg5 26. Qxg5+ Kh7 {, but} 27. Rxc8 Bxc8 ({if} 27...Rxc8 28. Qh6+ Kg8 29. Re5 f5 30. Rxe6 {crashes through}) 28. Qh5+ Kg8 29. Bh6f5 {and now the simplest is} 30. Qg6+ Kh8 31. Bxf8 {with a winning attack andextra material.}) 1-0[Event "2: Saint Louis"][Site "?"][Date "2015.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Giri, A."][Black "Grischuk, A."][Result "1-0"][ECO "D02"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "67"][EventDate "2015.??.??"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2017.08.07"]1. Nf3 {Giri's move order in this game is discussed in the Introduction to thebook.} d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. g3 Bb4+ $1 {Black intends to keep a pawn on d5,but before putting his bishop on e7 he gives a check.} 5. Bd2 {This is by farthe most popular response to Black's check.} ({Instead after} 5. Nc3 {theposition is more akin to a Nimzo-Indian rather than a Catalan.}) ({Meanwhilethe alternative} 5. Nbd2 {is discussed in Tari-Sjodahl in Chapter Four.}) 5...Be7 ({The bishop could also drop back to d6. For example,} 5... Bd6 6. Bg2 O-O7. O-O c6 8. b3 Nbd7 9. Nc3 Re8 10. Qc2 dxc4 