rily to leave Black with weaklings on c6 and c4 or e4. For example,} bxc4 14. bxc4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Ne5 $1 {with the initiative. ---Therefore Topalov settles for 11...Bb7 and looks for counterplay with a quick ...c6-c5.}) 12. Nbd2 {ANSWER: Not at all! Topalov's feint to play ...Ba6 meansthat Giri has been dissuaded from 11 Nc3 and opted for 11 Bc3, so his knightwill be developed to the inferior d2-square. --- Intending 13 e4 to gain spaceand so provoking Black's reply.} c5 13. Ne5 {Giri clears away the centre pawns,after which Black is almost equal but not quite equal – and we know all thesuffering that means for him in the Catalan.} cxd4 14. Bxd4 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Qc8 {The queen moves away from a potential pin on the d-file and dissolves a realpin on d5 by guarding the bishop on b7.} 16. Rac1 dxc4 17. Bxf6 ({White wantsthe e4-square for his queen as after} 17. Qxc4 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 ({the last chancefor} 18. Bxf6 $1) 18... Qb7+ {and 19...Rac8 equalizes for Black.}) 17... Bxf618. Qxc4 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Qb7+ 20. Qe4 Rfb8 {EXERCISE: Take the chance to examinethis position and try to list the factors that favour White. Which of these isWhite's best plan? (a) Play Rc6 to double up rooks on the c-file. (b) Exchangequeens and then bring the knight into the attack with Ne4. (c) Fix Black'spawns on dark squares with a2-a4 followed by exchanging queens then Nc4. ---ANSWER: White is slightly better. First we notice that he has control of thec-file. Less obvious is the fact that the white knight is stronger here thanthe black bishop. --- Everything else being equal, it is usually better tohave a bishop in an endgame, but here White's pawns are solid and compact.There is nothing for Black's bishop to attack as White's queenside pawns aresafely on light squares. --- Meanwhile Black's pawns on a5 and b6 are slightlyfragile. Despite the knight's superiority, Giri would be more than happy toexchange his knight for the bishop if in doing so he ties down Black's rooksto the defence of their queenside pawns. --- If you put Black's pawn back ona7 then it is difficult to see any advantage for White. If you put the pawnson a6 and b5 it also looks equal. However, with the pawns on a5 and b6 as inthe game, the b6-pawn is slightly vulnerable. It can be attacked in the longterm with Rc6 or Nc4. If Black advances it to b5 then it remains open toattack with Rc5. Then the further advance b3-b4 would leave Black with a weakpawn on a5 that could be attacked with Rc5 and Nc4. --- It might seem a tiny,almost nebulous advantage for White in the diagram position and, indeed,Topalov is very close to equality, but as you will see the former world numberone rated player was unable to defend it. If you play the Catalan you have tobelieve in small advantages. It is a question of having patience andself-belief.} 21. Rc6 ({Upon} 21. a4 b5 {the exchange of pawns eases Black'spath to equality. White will be left with his own vulnerable pawn on b3 after}22. axb5 Qxb5 {, or on a4 if he allows an exchange there.}) 21... Qd7 {Anexcellent riposte.} ({Now} 21... Qd7 22. Rxb6 $2 {is a trick to win a pawnthat rebounds after} Rd8 {, leaving White in a nasty pin along the d-file. Forexample,} 23. Rc6 Rac8 24. Rxc8 Qxc8 {and White has great difficulty inuntangling his pieces for if} 25. Qb1 Qd7 {reinforces the pin. You shouldalways look for ways to sacrifice a pawn to gain the initiative.}) 22. Rcc1 {Most players hate to lose face by admitting they have made a mistake or beenoutfoxed by the opponent. They press on regardless with a plan, even when itleads them into disaster or, as here, the loss of advantage. In fact this isone of the main ways that strong players lose games. There is a proverb thatRussian authors love to quote: 'Once you've said A, you have to say B'. It isthe equivalent of the English expression 'In for a penny, in for a pound'.However, having said 'A' with 21 Rc6, Giri has the strength of mind not to say'B' with 22 Rxb6.} Qb7 23. Qxb7 {Correcting his imprecise 21st move. Thisfinally confirms that in the exercise at move 20, the right answer was 'b'.Though don't worry too much if you didn't choose this plan as it took Giri twogoes to find it!} Rxb7 24. Ne4 {A paradox. The best square for the whiteknight is c4. Therefore White moves it to e4! The point is the knight can takea scenic route to c4, disrupting the Black pieces in the process.} Be7 {Otherwise, White can break up Black's kingside with Nxf6+ gxf6, then put hisrook on c6, leaving Black will a gloomy defence.} 25. Nd6 Rd7 {Likewise Blackfaces a miserable defence after Bxd6 Rxb6. Capablanca said you should makeyour opponent use his rooks to defend pawns in endgames .} ({Likewise, Blackfaces a miserable defence after} 25... Bxd6 26. Rxd6 {as his rooks are tieddown to the defence of his b-pawn.}) 26. Nc4 {The knight arrives at c4 havingcajoled the black rook into moving away from the defence of b6.} Rxd1 27. Rxd1b5 28. Ne5 Bf6 29. Nd7 a4 {It looks like Topalov has made a lot of progress.There isn't much to fear in the endgame after 30 Nxf6+ gxf6: Black wouldexchange with ...a4xb3 and then after a2xb3 attack b3 with ...Ra3 before Whitecan organize an attack on the b5-pawn with Rd7 and Rb7.} 30. Rc1 {A simple butvital move.} ({Now after} 30. Rc1 axb3 31. axb3 {Black can't attack b3 with}Ra3 {as} 32. Rc8+ {would mate. Therefore White would be the first to attack apawn on the b-file with Rc5 which would keep the initiative or even win thepawn.}) 30... axb3 31. axb3 Be7 32. Rc7 Rd8 33. Rb7 Bd6 {If Black were obligedto play ...b5-b4, the white knight could retreat via b6 and c4, with the planof Na5 and Nc6, picking up the pawn. Alternatively, the white king might jointhe attack on the pawn, eventually reaching c4. But as things stand, attackand defence have reached an equilibrium on the queenside: the b5-pawn can't bedirectly defended. On the other hand, the white rook has to stay guarding theknight. If the horse is moved to b6 it blocks the attack on b4. And besides,how can the knight escape as the squares a4, c4 and d5 are all guarded byBlack's pawns? --- EXERCISE: It looks as if Topalov has set up an unbreakabledefensive formation, but he has reckoned without Giri's plan. What can Whitedo to improve his position? --- ANSWER:} 34. g4 {It turns out that Black'sset-up is impregnable to White's pieces, but not to White's pawns. Clubplayers are often in too much of a hurry. In looking for ways to land blowswith their pieces, they miss the chance to wear down their opponent slowlywith their pawns. And yet how often do you see a strategy that doesn't requirethe use of pawns at some point? --- Giri plans to push his kingside pawnsforward with moves like e2-e3, f2-f4, h2-h4-h5 and g4-g5, etc. The pawns canbe supported by the king. If holes appear in the black kingside structure,such as if h5-h6 eliminates or displaces the g7-pawn, then the white knightcan escape via f6, when b5 drops or is forced to advance to b4, after which itbecomes a prey to the white knight and rook. Alternatively, once he has a pawnon f4 and his king on e4, White has the option of Ne5, again rescuing hisknight and leaving the b5-pawn in grave danger.} h5 {It is very unpleasant tojust sit and wait for White's attack. Therefore Topalov lashes out. With thegame move he wants to reduce the pawn front on the kingside – everything elsebeing equal this will increase his drawing chances. He also clears theh7-square for his king.} 35. gxh5 {Black probably underestimated this capture.}Kh7 {If nothing happens Black will play ...Kh6 and ...f7-f5, and then ...Kxh5 (he plays ...f7-f5 so that Rxb5+ doesn't come with check). Black would thenhave a good game. White therefore needs a way to get his knight from d7 sothat Rxb5 becomes possible.} 36. b4 $1 {A brilliant move. It looks totallycounterintuitive to put a pawn on a dark square. The point is White iscreating an escape square on c5 for his knight.} Bxb4 ({After} 36... Kh6 37.Nc5 Bxc5 38. bxc5 {it's hopeless for Black as b5 and f7 are both hanging.}) 37.Ne5 {Now the threat of 38 Nc6 with a lethal fork obliges Black to give up hisf7-pawn.} ({Instead} 37. Rxb5 Rxd7 38. Rxb4 Kh6 {is just equal.}) 37... Rd5 {If Black could jettison the b5-pawn, but keep his pawns on e6, f7 and g7intact he would have drawing chances.} ({Alas for him he has no good way todefend the f7-pawn, as} 37... f6 38. Nc6 {costs a piece.}) 38. Nxf7 Rxh5 {Black now has three isolated pawns and his rook is tied down to the defence ofb5. --- EXERCISE: Still on the theme of pawns, how can White energize hisknight?} ({Nonetheless he might emerge with the better game if he is given thechance to consolidate his passed pawn with} 38... Bc3 $1 {and 39...b4, whenhis rook is freed from defensive duty.}) 39. f4 {ANSWER: Giri makes brilliantuse of his limited material resources. With this new pawn thrust he creates anew base for the knight on e5 or on g5 from where it attacks e6 and cuts offthe rook on h5 from the defence of b5.} Kg6 40. Ne5+ Kh7 ({White wins upon} 40... Kf5 41. Rxb5 Kxf4 42. Nd3+ {.}) 41. Nf7 Kg6 42. Ne5+ Kh7 43. Nf3 {White is not satisfied with 43.Rxb5 Bd2} ({Giri isn't satisfied with} 43. Rxb5Bd2 {when he can't hold on to his f4-pawn without giving up h2. Therefore heretreats his knight to f3 to defend h2.}) 43... Rf5 {This leads to the loss ofthe e-pawn when it is hopeless for Black,} ({but after} 43... Kg6 44. Kg3 {White edges forwards leaving Black with a horrendous defence: for example,} Bc345. Kg4 b4 46. Rb6 Rd5 47. Ng5 Bf6 48. Nxe6 {and again the e-pawn has dropped.}) 44. Ng5+ Kh6 45. Kf3 Bd2 ({Alternatively,} 45... e5 46. Nf7+ Kh7 47. Nxe5 {.}) 46. e3 b4 47. Nxe6 Rh5 48. Nxg7 Rxh2 {With a little care the connectedpassed pawns will decide the day for White.} 49. Nf5+ Kg6 50. Ne7+ Kf6 51. Nd5+Ke6 52. Ke4 ({But not} 52. Nxb4 Rh3+ {when Black wins the e-pawn.}) 52... Rh353. Rb6+ Kd7 54. Kd3 Bc1 55. Rxb4 Kd6 56. Kd4 {. A hard positional struggle inwhich Giri showed how to carry a small opening advantage over into the endgame.} 1-0[Event "4: Huai'an (rapid)"][Site "?"][Date "2016.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Li Chao"][Black "Fressinet, L."][Result "1-0"][ECO "E01"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "63"][EventDate "2016.??.??"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2017.08.07"]1. d4 ({As usual in the Catalan, transpositions are rife. For example, theBotvinnik game in the notes to 11 Be3 began life} 1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 Nf64. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. d4 Nbd7 7. Qc2 c6 8. Bf4 Ne4 9. Nc3 g5 10. Bc1 f5 {;})({while the game Li Chao-Bellin in the notes to 10...g5 started as a Dutch with} 1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d5 7. Nc3 c6 8. Qc2Ne4 9. Bf4 Nd7 10. Rad1 g5 11. Bc1 {, etc. Notice in both cases there were no ...Bb4+ and Bd2 moves thrown in, as occur below with 4...Bb4+ and 5 Bd2.Therefore the move numbers in the Botvinnik and Bellin games are one behindthose in the main game.}) 1... d5 ({I have 'tidied up' the move order for thesake of clarity. This game really began with the sequence} 1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.g3 d5 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Nf3 O-O {, etc.}) 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3Bb4+ {QUESTION: If I adopt the Catalan move order as Black intending to reacha Dutch set-up, should I begin with ...Bb4+ to make White go Bd2, or play ...Be7 straightaway? --- ANSWER: Well, in the main game Li Chao makes White'sposition look good answering ...Bb4+ with Bd2 and then after the retreat ...Be7 playing Bf4. So there's no real difference here: the white bishop couldhave gone straight from c1 to f4, or via d2, while the black bishop on e7could have gone straight from f8 or via b4. The only difference shows up inthe number of moves. --- Overall I would say don't play 4...Bb4+. Whiteprobably won't gain anything from having his bishop on d2 rather than c1, butthere's no reason to give him extra possibilities.} ({A sequence withindependent value involves Black deferring castling kingside to enhance hiskingside attacking chances. The imaginative attacking player Richard Rapporthas essayed} 4... Be7 5. Bg2 Ne4 6. O-O f5 7. Nc3 c6 {.} {Instead, the moreactive} 8. Ne5 ({If now} 8. Qc2 {, I assume that Rapport's idea is somethinglike} Nd7 9. Bf4 g5 10. Be3 h5 11. Qc1 Rg8 {with a scary-looking assaultbrewing on the kingside.} (11... --)) 8... Nd7 9. Nxd7 Bxd7 10. Nxe4 fxe4 11.Bf4 {removes any danger of a black pawn storm. After} O-O 12. e3 {White had aslight edge in A.Ipatov-R.Rapport, German League 2015. Notably his bishop isactive on f4 outside his pawn chain and he is ready to open the f-file withf2-f3. And again we see that White plays Bf4. The bishop could have comedirectly from c1 or via d2 after the ...Bb4+ move order}) 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qc2 Ne4 {Rather than play solidly with 8...c6 Black decides ona Stonewall Dutch approach.} 9. Bf4 ({White avoids the exchange of his bishopfor the knight as would occur after, say,} 9. Nc3 {when} Nxd2 10. Nxd2 ({instead he threatens to win a pawn with} 10. cxd5) 10... c6 {isn't much forWhite.}) 9... c6 ({QUESTION: What happens if} 9... g5 {to drive away thebishop? --- ANSWER: The bishop isn't going anywhere after 9...g5? –} 10. cxd5$1 {threatens 11 Bxc7, when} gxf4 11. Qxe4 {leaves the black kingsidefractured.}) 10. Nc3 g5 $5 {Here, however, this move is tactically watertight.The first thing to note is that 11 Nxe4?? now loses a piece after 11...dxe4.--- EXERCISE: Can you guess which one, and what the idea is behind putting iton that square?} ({Instead, supporting e4 with} 10... Ndf6 $6 {does nothing tovitalize Black's game and gives White a pleasant advantage after} 11. Ne5 {.})({The colourless exchange} 10... Nxc3 $6 11. Qxc3 {also leaves Black passive.Therefore he has a choice of pawn moves: he can either defend e4 or attack f4.The game move has been used by two world champions (see below), but Li Chaocasts the whole line in a rather dubious light for Black.}) ({Li Chao has alsocrushed Black's other move after} 10... f5 11. Rad1 g5 12. Bc1 {. This is atleast a moral victory for White compared to 11 Bc1 in the next note, as he hasgot his rook from a1 to d1 before retreating his bishop (though 12 Be3 alsohas its fans, for example Eljanov). Here's a drastic example of White'sattacking chances:} Nd6 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Ne5 Nb6 ({maybe Black should try} 14... Nf7 {so the knight helps out the vulnerable kingside}) 15. g4 $1 {(a strong pawn stab; Black already looks in trouble)} Ne4 16. Nxe4 fxe4 17. f3{(the standard move to open lines)} exf3 18. exf3 Nd7 19. Ng6 $1 {(a neattactical blow; if Black refuses the knight his already crumbling defences willbe deprived of the vital dark-squared bishop with 20 Nxe7+)} hxg6 20. Qxg6+ Kh821. f4 {(intending to mate with 22 Rf3 and 23 Rh3+)} Qe8 22. Qh6+ Kg8 23. f5Rf6 24. Qxg5+ {1-0, Li Chao-R.Bellin, Gibraltar 2016 (if} Kh8 ({or} 24... Kf825. fxe6 {quickly massacre the black king}) 25. Rf3 {. With the text, Blackavoids 10...f5 as he wants to use the f5-square for one of his pieces in theevent of White replying with 11 Be3.}) 11. Be3 {An active retreat.} ({It ispossible to have some sympathy for} 11. Bc1 {, even though it would shut inthe rook on a1. A 1963 world championship matchgame between Petrosian andBotvinnik then continued} f5 12. b3 {, and here} Nd6 {has been suggested,answering} ({the actual game went} 12... Bf6 13. Bb2 {, when} Qe7 {followed by14...Qg7 might have been best; Botvinnik settled for 13...Bg7 with the gamedrawn after mutual errors}) 13. Ne5 {with} Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nf7 {, whichsolidifies the black kingside. --- By the way, if you look up this game you'llfind that the move numbers are one behind those in the present game, asBotvinnik didn't indulge in any of the 'nonsense' with ...Bb4+ and ...Be7, butrather put his bishop on e7 straightaway, and Petrosian's bishop went expressfrom c1 to f4 with no stopping off on d2.}) 11... Nd6 ({ANSWER: As White haschosen the e3-square for his bishop, Black renounces} 11... f5 {. Instead heplans to reroute his knight to f5 and snaffle White's dark-squared bishop. Hehopes that the bishop pair and the resulting damage to White's pawn structurewill give him sufficient counterplay.}) 12. cxd5 ({When this position wasreached in P.Eljanov-M.Carlsen, Wijk aan Zee 2016, White dawdled with} 12. b3 {, which let the world champion complicate matters with} Nf5 13. g4 Nxe3 14.fxe3 b5 $1 {. Li Chao chooses a more direct plan.}) 12... cxd5 13. Qc1 $1 {A sly retreat of the queen. When he was world champion Karpov could dominatehis opponents by making little queen moves on the first rank, and it seemssome of the magic has rubbed off on Li Chao. Rather than an attacking weapon,the pawn on g5 is exposed as a liability.} h6 ({Note that after} 13... f6 {Black has compromised his pawn structure in the centre;}) ({while the pawn ong4 is out on a limb after} 13... g4 14. Ne5 {.}) 14. h4 $1 {White will breakopen the h-file in order to start a direct attack against the black king.} Nf5({Black plays to eliminate the bishop on e3 as} 14... gxh4 15. Bxh6 {, with 16Qf4 looming, is clearly unacceptable for him.}) 15. hxg5 Nxe3 {Completing theplan begun with 11...Nd6, but White has the better chances.} 16. Qxe3 {Anothergood feature of 12 cxd5 cxd5 13 Qc1, compared to 12 b3 in the Eljanov gamementioned above, is that White is able to keep his pawn structure tidy andcentralize his queen on e3. Here she is unassailable and can support an attackon the kingside.} hxg5 17. Bh3 {Step by step White's plan unfolds on thekingside: all barriers are removed to get a rook to h1.} Kg7 18. Kg2 Nb6 19. b3{A quiet move to stop Nc4. --- QUESTION: Does this slow White's build-up? ---ANSWER: Maybe, but he is pleased to see the black knight head away from thekingside.} Rh8 20. Rh1 {White finally gets his rook