...b7-b5 tohold on to the c4-pawn. He also has more space in the centre and potentiallymobile pawns there. In return Black has an extra pawn. He has the chance tobuild up on the queenside with moves like ...b7-b5 and Rb8.} 8. e3 $1 {Anexample of a concrete handling of the problems of the opening. It seemsstrange that Grischuk would want to defend the d4-pawn again instead of, say,developing his queen's knight. In fact the modest looking-pawn move is aclever prophylactic stroke.} ({As} 8. e3 b5 {, loses the exchange after} ({Black would like to begin} 8... Rb8 {and only then 9...b5}) 9. Ne5 Nxe5 10.Bxa8 {for insufficient play.}) ({This plan would have worked well after theroutine} 8. Nc3 {by White. --- EXERCISE: How does Grischuk's little pawn movein the game spoil this ...Rb8 and ...b7-b5 plan for Black? --- ANSWER: If} Rb8{White can unexpectedly reply} 9. Nd2 $1 {. Then} b5 {would leave c6 hanging;}({while} 9... Na5 {is useless after} 10. Qa4+ Nc6 11. Qxc4 {. Therefore Blackwould be unable to defend the c4-pawn. White would regain it with some edgeafter 10 Nxc4, when Black has conceded the centre and put the rook on b8 forno good reason.})) 8... Bd7 {With the game move Potkin defends c6 at once,making ...b7-b5 possible. This, however, is a little victory for White asBlack would rather have left the bishop on c8 for the time being or elseplayed it to b7 after ...b7-b5. On d7 it is passively placed and blocks thequeen's influence on the d-file.} 9. Nc3 {Only now, after White has extractedthe move ...Bd7 from Black.} O-O 10. Rc1 Rb8 {At first glance it looks likeBlack is doing well as he is ready to support his extra pawn with ...b7-b5.Meanwhile nothing is happening in the centre to scare him. The way Grischukgains control of the position will therefore come as a surprise to those notacquainted with this type of pawn structure.} 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 {A difficultdecision. --- EXERCISE: After the bishop recapture can you work out White'sstrategy? Where is he going to attack - on the queenside, in the centre oron the kingside?} ({There is a lot to be said for} 11... gxf6 {as the pawn onf6 keeps e5 guarded and the dark-squared bishop remains on e7 where itcontrols some important squares. However, White could try to exploit theevident damage to Black's kingside structure with} 12. Nd2 $5 b5 13. Qh5 {whenhis king is uncomfortable and the white queen very well placed. Still, I thinkI prefer 11...gxf6 as it offers more counterplay in this line after} f5 {thanBlack achieves in the game.}) 12. Ne4 {The knight enters the fray and uncoversan attack on c4.} b5 {Black holds on to his pawn, but now Grischuk's plan isrevealed.} 13. b3 $1 {ANSWER: This is it! In answer to the question aboveabout where White is going to attack, the answer is everywhere: on thequeenside, in the centre and on the kingside. However, first of all heundermines Black's queenside pawns. Imagine if Black now plays 13...cxb3.After 14 axb3 in reply we have the diagram position below. --- It's importantto grasp the nature of White's strategic pawn sacrifice, as it will occur invarious lines where Black has played an early ...d5xc4 and held on to the pawn.--- Black is still a pawn up. However, his queenside structure has lost almostall its dynamism with the disappearance of the c4-pawn. Instead of threateningto roll forwards en masse, the pawns are a liability and will need defendingby the pieces. Things are particularly awkward as White has a rook bearingdown along the c-file at the vulnerable knight and beyond it the backward pawnon c7. --- There is also a nasty hole on the c5-square which is inviting forWhite's knight. However, Black can play 14...Be7 and be ready to exchange offthe knight for his bishop when it sets foot on c5. So we could refine White'splay after 13...cxb3 with the interpolation 14 Nxf6+ Qxf6 and only then 15axb3. Then Black's defences along the c-file have been weakened as the blackqueen has been deflected from d8 where it defended c7. --- A case could alsobe made for 14 Nxf6+ Qxf6 15 Qxb3. White could then follow up with Rc5 anddouble rooks along the c-file, with the white queen perhaps going to a3 toattack a6. A possible drawback to retaking on b3 with the queen is that thec4-square isn't defended, so White would have to watch out for ...Na5 and ...Nc4 by Black. --- Whether White recaptures with the queen or pawn, orinterposes 14 Nxf6+ Qxf6 or not, he has full compensation for the pawn deficit.In fact his game is preferable, or at least easier to play, as sooner or laterhe is likely to regain his pawn whilst keeping the initiative.} Be7 {Ratherthan assume a defensive attitude Potkin decides to return the pawn. He hopesthat the activity of his rook on b8 and minor pieces will compensate for theinferiority of his pawn structure.} 14. bxc4 bxc4 15. Rxc4 Nb4 {EXERCISE: Howcan White meet the double threat of 15...Nxa2 and 16...Bb5, winning theexchange? --- ANSWER:} 16. a4 $1 {Killing two birds with one stone. But Blackpersists in attacking a4.} Qe8 17. Nc3 Nc6 $2 {Black goes passive at the wrongmoment.} ({He should have persevered with his attack on a4 with} 17... Nd5 $1 {. Then after} 18. Nxd5 $1 ({White might also try} 18. Qa1) ({or} 18. Ne5) 18...exd5 19. Rxc7 Bd6 20. Ra7 Bxa4 21. Qa1 Rb6 22. Ne5 {an unbalanced situationarises. White is attacking d5 and has the initiative in the centre, butBlack's bishop pair shouldn't be underestimated. --- My computer programsuggests the following sequence:} Bb5 23. Nxf7 $1 Qe6 $1 ({not} 23... Rxf7 24.Bxd5 {, when f7 can't be defended in a safe way: for example,} Bd7 ({or} 24...Be7 25. Rc1 {with the threat of 26 Rcc7 and a decisive initiative}) 25. Qa2 {, intending to take twice on f7 then on d7}) 24. Nxd6 Bxf1 25. Bxf1 Qxd6 26.Qa2 {and White has a pawn and pressure for the exchange. The computer thenwants to call it a draw with} Rf7 27. Ra8+ Rf8 28. Ra7 Rf7 {, etc.}) 18. d5 $1exd5 ({Black can't prevent a white knight taking up a commanding centreposition, as if} 18... Nb4 19. Ne5 $1 {follows.}) 19. Nxd5 Bd6 20. Qc2 Na5 {EXERCISE: How should White pursue his attack? --- ANSWER:} 21. Rh4 $1 {Exactly.It seems that Potkin was so focused on the queenside and how to gaincounterplay to offset the weakness of c7, he forgot he had a king. It is verylogical for White to switch to a direct kingside attack, as Black's threeminor pieces, especially the knight, are a long way off and his queen isn'twell positioned for the defence either. It turns out Black's last move was amistake. He should have played 20...h6!, when 21 Rh4 Qd8 leads to nothingclear for White. Therefore White should continue more modestly with 21 Nd4,when 21...Nxd4 22 Rxd4 leaves Black suffering because of the weakness on c7.}h6 ({Black has no good way to shield h7. For example,} 21... g6 {loses thequeen to a fork on f6;}) ({while if} 21... f5 22. Qc3 $1 {(gaining time to setup a winning sequence by attacking the black knight)} Nc6 23. Ng5 h6 24. Nxc7$1 Bxc7 25. Bd5+ Kh8 {(losing at once, but interposing on f7 loses oodles ofmaterial)} 26. Rxh6# {.}) 22. Rxh6 {Exploiting the potential fork on f6.Black's position is falling apart all over the board. His king's defences arefull of holes and his pawns and pieces are mostly hanging.} f5 23. Rh4 Nb3 24.Nxc7 Qe7 25. Ng5 $1 {The most energetic way to finish the game is to clear theway for the Catalan bishop to join in the attack.} Qxg5 26. Bd5+ Rf7 27. Qc4Rbf8 ({If} 27... Qf6 28. Bxf7+ Qxf7 29. Rh8+ {wins the black queen.}) 28. Qxb3Bxc7 29. Rd1 ({More accurate was} 29. Bxf7+ Rxf7 30. Rh8+ Kxh8 31. Qxf7 {,when Black loses a bishop, leaving him far too much material down -} Qd832. Rd1 {wouldn't help him.}) 29... Be8 30. Qc4 Be5 ({Anyhow Black drops thebishop, but after, say,} 30... Bd8 31. Qxa6 {White is still winning.}) 31. f4Qe7 32. fxe5 Qxe5 33. Qd4 {Grischuk can take it easy as he will be theexchange and a pawn up.} Qe7 34. Rf4 g6 35. e4 ({It's hard to criticise a movethat makes your opponent resign, though it should be mentioned that} 35. Rh4 {would force Black to give up his queen at once to avoid mate on h8.Nonetheless this was an excellent game by Grischuk who combined queensidepressure with a kingside attack in masterly style.}) 1-0[Event "13: Chelyabinsk (rapid)"][Site "?"][Date "2016.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Smirnov, P."][Black "Kosyrev, V."][Result "1-0"][ECO "E04"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "51"][EventDate "2016.??.??"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2017.08.07"]1. d4 e6 2. c4 Nf6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Nf3 a6 6. Ne5 {Since 6 Ne5 gets anexclamation mark in games in this chapter versus 5...b5 and 5...c6, itcertainly deserves to be considered here. The obvious good point is that itstops both 6...b5 and 6...Nc6.} c5 $5 {However, this is a somewhat annoyingreply. Black renounces the plan of holding on to the c4-pawn with ...b7-b5 inorder to counterattack against the white centre. It is all the more effectiveas White's previous move has delayed his development and removed a defenderfrom d4.} ({A sharp alternative for Black is} 6... Bb4+ 7. Nc3 Nd5 8. Bd2 b5 {. The pressure on c3 has allowed Black to consolidate his extra pawn. However,White gains compensation in the shape of the two bishops and a mobile centre:}9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. a4 f6 12. Ng4 Bb7 13. Qb1 $1 {(a neat way to putpressure on b5)} Qe8 14. e4 Nb6 15. Ne3 Bc6 {. So far this is A.Huzman-O.Dancevski, Skopje 2015, and now} ({thanks to the queen on b1 if} 15... Nxa4 $216. Rxa4 bxa4 17. Qxb7 {wins material for White}) 16. d5 {would have givenWhite a strong initiative.}) 7. Be3 $5 {An awkward-looking, but effective move.Again and again in the Catalan we see White lavish time and care on hisfavourite light-squared bishop, while leaving the dirty jobs to hisdark-squared bishop. Here it guards the d4-pawn and shows a willingness toexchange for a knight.