lso clear the b7-square for his bishop. Nonetheless playremains sharp: for example,} 7. a4 ({or equally} 7. Ne5 Bb7 8. a4) 7... Bb7 8.Ne5 {and play has transposed to the note on 8 a4 in Game 15. Complicated,isn't it?}) ({Another option is} 6. a4 {A final choice is} c5 {(a radicallydifferent approach, switching from a Slav set-up to an attack on d4)} ({whenafter} 6... b5 $6 7. Ne5 Nd5 {(to meet the double threat of 8 Nxc6 and 8 axb5),White has a favourable situation whereby the black knight has been enticed tod5 without Nc3 having been played. See, for example, the Kantor-Rydstrom gameabove. The knight can be driven back after} 8. O-O {with a well-timed e2-e4,without Black having the option of a timesaving ...Nxc3 exchange.} (8. --)) ({Alternatively, Black can try} 6... Bb4+ 7. Bd2 {(in contrast to the main gamethere is no option of ...Qxd4 for Black)} a5 8. Qc2 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 $5 {and wehave transposed to Hammer-Carlsen given in the note to 7 a3 in Wagner-Brkic inChapter Four.}) 7. O-O Nc6 {. White doesn't have the option of Qa4 to putpressure on the knight on c6 in the style of Caruana-Naiditsch in Chapter Fouras the a4-pawn blocks the square, but after} 8. dxc5 Qxd1 ({perhaps} 8... Qc7 {should be preferred}) 9. Rxd1 Bxc5 10. Nbd2 c3 ({White also regains the pawnupon} 10... Na5 11. Ne5) 11. bxc3 O-O 12. Nb3 Be7 13. Nfd4 Bd7 14. Ba3 Bxa3 15.Rxa3 {White has a small plus. --- The variations in this game, with theirreferences to other chapters, illustrate the many transpositionalpossibilities in the Catalan.}) 6... Bb4+ {Black seeks to disrupt White'sbuild-up with a bishop check in the style of Chapter Four.} 7. Bd2 {Showing areadiness to sacrifice a couple of pawns for an attack. I think White'schances are excellent.} ({Also possible was} 7. Nc3 Nd5 8. Bd2 {which alsolooks pretty good for him.}) 7... Qxd4 {The consistent move.} ({After} 7...Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 {followed by Na3 and Nxc4 White has the edge. Instead Blackgrabs a second pawn.}) 8. Bxb4 Qxe5 9. Na3 b5 10. Bd6 $1 {QUESTION: Could youuse this drawing method versus Kramnik!? --- ANSWER: No. Better to play a fulllength game and savour the chance to play a former world champion even if youlose.} ({Here} 10. f4 $5 {is a strange-looking move which aims to drive awaythe black queen so that the knight can capture on b5. However, after anexchange sacrifice Black looks okay:} Qc7 11. Nxb5 cxb5 12. Bxa8 Bb7 13. Bxb7Qxb7 14. O-O Qb6+ 15. Kh1 {and here Stockfish suggests} Ne4 $5 {intending ...a7-a5 (to drive away the white bishop to be able to castle) as unclear.}) ({Meanwhile Grischuk has used this peaceful sequence versus Kramnik:} 10. Bc3 Qc5{(here the black queen has to stay on a square where she rules out Nxb5)} 11.Bd4 Qb4+ 12. Bc3 Qc5 13. Bd4 {with a repetition.}) 10... Qxb2 11. O-O {EXERCISE: Assess the size of White's compensation for the three pawns. Whatare his threats? --- ANSWER: White has a sizeable lead in development. Hisking is safely castled whilst its opposite number is stuck in the centre. Thiswouldn't matter too much if lines were closed, but here the d-file is open.Already Black has to contend with ideas such as Bxb8, removing the defender ofc6 and clearing the way for both Bxc6+ and Qd6; not that White would hurry toexchange off his fabulous bishop which keeps the black king stranded on e8.The black queen is also an attractive target, with ideas of Rb1 and then Nxb5afoot. --- Hence Black blocks the d-file and the long diagonal towards c6 anda8 with his knight. This is the only way he can hope to survive.} Nd5 $1 12. e4{Driving away the knight.} ({Stockfish prefers to delay this for a move toallow the white queen to infiltrate on the dark squares via d2 and g5:} 12. Nc2$5 Bb7 13. e4 Nc3 14. Qd2 c5 {(the threat was 15 Ba3 winning a knight)} (14...h6 15. Ba3 {win}) 15. Qg5 Nc6 16. e5 {(intending 17 Bxc6+ Bxc6 18 Qe7 mate)}Ne2+ 17. Kh1 {and here after} Qxc2 ({so} 17... h6 {is needed to dislodge thewhite queen, when} 18. Qxg7 O-O-O 19. Qxf7 Rd7 20. Qg6 {looks like excellentpractical chances for White due to the weaknesses on e6 and Black's disjointedqueenside}) 18. Bxc6+ $3 Bxc6+ 19. f3 {, rather surprisingly White mates innine moves at the latest!}) 12... Nc3 13. Qh5 ({Also possible was} 13. Qg4 {;})({but not} 13. Qd4 $4 {due to an unpleasant check on e2.}) 13... h6 14. e5 Bd715. Rae1 {White has no need to hurry. The black king won't find a safe refugein the centre or on either wing.} Na6 16. Qf3 Nd5 17. Qg4 Nab4 $2 {It's nosurprise that Black collapses in such an unpleasant position.} ({Moretenacious was} 17... Rg8 {holding on to the g7-pawn, though it's not much funfor Black after, say,} 18. Rb1 Qc3 19. Rfc1 Qa5 20. Nc2 {intending 21 Nd4,when he is under permanent pressure.}) 18. Qxg7 O-O-O {Perhaps Black thoughthe had escaped the worst here, but:} 19. Nxc4 $1 {I feel a cliché coming on: aknight on the rim isn't always dim.} ({This is a crushing move as} 19. Nxc4bxc4 20. Rb1 {leads to fatal threats of mate along the open b-file: forinstance,} Qc3 21. Bxd5 exd5 ({or} 21... Nxd5 22. Rb8#) 22. Rxb4 {and Blackhas to give up his queen to avert mate, as after} Be6 23. Rb8+ Kd7 24. Qf6 $1Rxb8 ({or} 24... Rhe8 25. Rxd8+) ({or - the nicest -} 24... Rde8 25. Rd8+ Rxd826. Qe7+ {and mates}) 25. Qe7+ Kc8 26. Qc7# {.}) 19... Qxa2 20. Ne3 {Withideas of 21 Ra1 and 22 Rxa7. The fact that White's 'bad' knight is now fullyinvolved in the struggle tilts the game decisively in his favour.} Nxe3 21.Rxe3 Nc2 22. Rd3 {Planning 23 Rfd1 combined with Qxf7 and Be7 to put fatalpressure on d7.} b4 23. Qxf7 Qc4 24. Rfd1 b3 25. Qf3 {Going after theindefensible b3-pawn.} ({Black's last hope was a swindle with} 25. Be7 b2 26.Bxd8 $2 ({though even in this sequence} 26. Bf1 {wins for White}) 26... Qxd3 $1{.}) 25... Nb4 26. Rd4 {. Winning the knight followed by a quick mate. Anexample of the extreme dangers Black faces in this line.} 1-0[Event "15: Doha"][Site "?"][Date "2014.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Kramnik, V."][Black "Giri, A."][Result "1-0"][ECO "D43"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "73"][EventDate "2014.??.??"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2017.08.07"]1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {I should point out that I have changed the move order forthe first ten (!) moves.} ({Another move order for Black to avoid being forcedinto ...Nd5 is to delay the pawn move ...e7-e6. Thus S.Mamedyarov-A.Beliavsky,Reykjavik 2016, went} 2... c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 b5 6. b3 {(gettingthe pawn stab in early)} cxb3 7. axb3 e6 8. O-O Be7 9. Ne5 Bb7 10. Nc3 {and wehave reached the position in the main game.}) ({Finally, here is a third moveorder which was the way the Kramnik-Giri game actually began:} 2... c6 3. Nf3Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 dxc4 6. Bg2 b5 7. Ne5 a6 8. O-O (8. Nxc6 $2 Qb6 9. Ne5 Bb7)8... Bb7 9. b3 cxb3 10. axb3 Be7 {. Because the game begins as a Slav with 4Nc3 thrown in, White is slower getting in the move Ne5 to put pressure onBlack's queenside. Giri for his part leaves c6 hanging for a move with 7...a6 (as he doesn't fear the line 8 Nxc6? Qb6 which is good for Black after 9 Ne5Bb7, etc), Kramnik replies 8 0-0 and then Black defends c6 with 8...Bb7. ---The changed move order I have given has been used in top-class games, such asthe Eljanov-Tomashevsky game in this note.}) 3. Nf3 c6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 b5 {Black begins the game with a series of pawn moves. By delaying ...Nf6 he getsin ...dxc4 and ...b7-b5 before White has the chance to play Ne5. This meansthat he isn't obliged to put his knight on d5 to block the long diagonal, aswas the case in the Kantor and Eljanov games. This is of great significancesince not only did the knight's move use up a precious tempo, on d5 it becamea target for White's e2-e4 centre push.} 6. Ne5 {Our familiar knight move tobegin an assault on c6.} Bb7 7. O-O Nf6 {Black finally develops the knighthaving used the delay to bolster his queenside defences. Nonetheless he stillhas an uncomfortable position after White's next move.} 8. b3 {A typical motifin this variation: White prises open the a-file and c-file so that he can putpressure on the fragile black queenside structure. He has good compensationfor his pawn. In fact when Kramnik is White it feels like a forced loss forBlack. Such is the power of the former World Champion's technique.} ({Weshould also take a look at} 8. a4 {. This isn't so much fun for White as inthe Kantor and Eljanov games as Black hasn't got a vulnerable knight on d5 tohit by e2-e4. Also with no knight on d5 the d4-pawn isn't sheltered, so thatif White plays b2-b3 and answers ...c5xb3 with Qxb3 Black sometimes has theoption of ...Qxd4. --- Eagle-eyed readers will have noticed that play hastransposed to a note in Game 14 above where play began 3...Nf6 4 g3 dxc4 5 Bg2c6 (see the comments to 6 Ne5 and the line 6 0-0 b5 7 a4 Bb7 8 Ne5). --- Let'sexamine some of the possibilities after 8 a4:} a6 $1 (8... Nd5 {would just bepoor for Black, when} 9. b3 cxb3 10. axb5 cxb5 11. Qxb3 a6 12. e4 {is Game 10all over again.}) (8... Qc8 9. b3 $5 {(similar to the main game; Black's lastmove means that ...Qxd4 is no longer an option for him in reply to Qxb3, sothis standard clearance move wins the b3-square for the white queen change to:and in the long term facilitates Rfc1 to strike at the c6-pawn)} cxb3 10. Qxb3{and White has pressure: for example,} a6 ({or} 10... b4 11. a5 {which cutsoff any defence of b4 with ...a7-a5}) 11. Nd2 b4 ({if} 11... Nbd7 12. Ba3 {isa typical idea for White to exchange off Black's 'good' bishop and weaken hisdark squares}) 12. Ndc4 {and Black remains uncomfortable on the queenside.}) (8... Qb6 9. b3 cxb3 10. Qxb3 {and now so the key question is can Black getaway with} Qxd4 {- ?} (10... Nbd7 11. Be3 $1 {just looks good for White:Black's queenside is under heavy siege and his queen herself a target of thebishop after 12 d5}) 11. Bb2 {. The answer seems a resounding 'no!'.} Qb6 12.Nd2 Nbd7 13. axb5 cxb5 14. Ndc4 $1 {, and if} bxc4 15. Qxb6 axb6 16. Bxb7 Rxa117. Rxa1 {is a winning attack for White}) (8... Qc7 9. b3 {(no surpriseanymore!)} cxb3 10. Qxb3 a6 11. Bf4 Bd6 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Bxa8 14. Nc3 b4({if} 14... O-O 15. Nxb5 $1 {and, for instance,} Qb6 16. Rb1) 15. Ra1 $1 {withan initiative for White.}) {Perhaps more testing is} 9. b3 $5 {in the style ofline 'a' above: for example,} ({Now} 9. Nc3 {(threatening to win a pawn backwith 10 axb5 axb5 11 Rxa8 Bxa8 12 Nxb5) can be met by} Nd5 (9... Qc8) ({or} 9... Qb6 {with unclear play.})) 9... cxb3 10. Bb2 {(guarding d4 beforerecapturing on b3 with the queen)} Nbd7 11. Qxb3 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Rd1 Qb614. Nd2 {and White intends to build up with Ne4 and Nd6. He has (just) enoughpressure for his pawn}) 8... cxb3 9. axb3 {Simple and good as it guaranteeslong-term pressure on the queenside.} ({Not} 9. Qxb3 $2 {when} Qxd4 10. Bb2 Qb6{is at best a dubious second sacrifice for White.}) 9... Be7 10. Nc3 a6 ({Instead, Black gave back the pawn at once but never quite equalized after} 10... O-O 11. Nxb5 Nd5 12. Na3 c5 13. Bb2 Nd7 14. Nac4 cxd4 15. Bxd4 Nxe5 16.Bxe5 {in P.Eljanov-E.Tomashevsky, Tsaghkadzor 2015.}) 11. Bb2 {A natural move.}({An alternative way to develop the bishop was} 11. Bg5 {.}) 11... O-O 12. Qc2{Kramnik begins his campaign of exerting piece pressure on the backward pawnon c6 and the vulnerable square in front of it.} Nfd7 {Giri challenges thewhite knight. --- EXERCISE: Which square does White want to dominate and howcan this be achieved?} ({Putting the queen's head in a lion's mouth doesn'tturn out well for Black after} 12... Qxd4 13. Nd5 Qc5 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Qxc5Bxc5 16. Ng4 Be7 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Bxf6 Nd7 19. Bc3 {. White has one bishopdominating the dark squares, the other one tying Black down to the c6-pawn.This is more than enough compensation for a pawn.}) ({Black could have offeredback the pawn with} 12... Nbd7 {, when after} 13. Nxc6 ({instead} 13. Nd3 $5Qb6 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Rfd8 16. Rfc1 Nf6 17. Bg2 a5 18. Nc5 {maintains asimilar edge to that in the game}) 13... Bxc6 14. Bxc6 Rc8 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 16.Qd3 Qb7 {and 17...Rfd8, Black had freed his game in A.Onischuk-T.RoussellRoozmon, Montreal 2009. I can't imagine Kramnik letting his opponent escape soeasily.}) 13. Nd3 $1 {ANSWER: Kramnik doesn't want to ease his opponent's gameby exchanges. Instead he retreats his knight in order to gain control over c5.The square in front of a backward pawn is always very attractive for a knightif it can be established safely there, as no enemy pawn can drive it away.} Qb614. Ne4 a5 15. Ndc5 {Mission accomplished.} Bc8 {QUESTION: Can we make Blackweaken his queenside pawns? ANSWER:} 16. Qc3 $1 {Remember Bobby Fischer'smaxim 'Look at the whole board!'. This threatens 17 d5 when mate looms on g7.}b4 ({If} 16... Nf6 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Ne4 $1 {is strong for White as} Be7 19.d5 f6 20. d6 {creates a strong passed pawn. Black's reply obliges the queen toretreat, but leaves his pawn structure disfigured.}) 17. Qe3 Na6 18. Rfc1 Nc7 ({It is normally a good idea when you have a backward pawn to plug the squarein front of it with an enemy pawn. By the same logic the opponent wants tooccupy the square with a piece, not a pawn. However, after} 18... Naxc5 19.dxc5 {Black doesn't escape the pressure because of} Qc7 20. Nd6 $1 {, usingthe c5-pawn as the support for a knight outpost deep in Black's territory. Theknight can't be removed as White's bishop pair would become devastating: forexample,} Bxd6 $2 21. cxd6 Qxd6 22. Bxc6 Ra6 23. Bb5 Ra8 24. Rd1 Qe7 25. Bxd7Bxd7 26. Qd4 {(threatening d7 and g7)} f6 27. Qxd7 {and wins.}) 19. Nxd7 Bxd720. Nc5 Be8 21. Ra2 {A useful move with no definite plan in mind. PerhapsWhite will double up rooks along the a-file, or drop his bishop back to a1 andthen switch his rook from a2 to c2 to add to the pressure on c6. In any caseit keeps Black guessing about where the attack is going to come from. ---There is no need to hurry when your opponent's pieces are tied up defendingpawns. If you wait a while he might become reckless and do your work for youby staging an unsuccessful break out.} Qb5 22. Qd3 $1 {An excellent strokewhich combines a fine positional sense with remarkable patience. Kramnik seesthat his opponent's queen is holding together his queenside and so offers itsexchange. He is confident that in the endgame he can not only regain his pawn,but retain enough pressure to cause Giri serious problems.} Qxd3 23. Nxd3 Nd524. Ne5 Ra6 {EXERCISE: Study this position and see if you can find Kramnik'sclever way of increasing the pressure. --- ANSWER:} 25. Bf1 $1 {A precise move.} ({If White had begun with} 25. e4 {to push back the knight, then after} Nc7 {or if White switched to the plan of capturing on a5 then his d4-pawn would beslightly fragile. For example,} 26. Rca1 ({, Black can meet} 26. Bf1 {with} Nb5$1 {;} (26... --)) 26... Nb5 27. Rxa5 Rxa5 28. Rxa5 f6 29. Nd3 Bf7 {and 30...Rd8 will follow, threatening the pawn.}) 25... Nc3 {Giri despairs of asuccessful defence and so gives up a couple of pawns in search of activity forhis bishops.} ({After} 25... Ra8 {White can play in the style of the game with}26. e4 Nc3 27. Bxc3 bxc3 28. Rxc3 {with a crushing advantage.}) 26. Bxc3 bxc327. Rxc3 c5 28. dxc5 Bf6 29. f4 Bb5 {Black intends to complete his piecedeployment with 30...Rc8 to oppose the advance of the c-pawn and even win it,but Kramnik defeats this plan.} 30. Bg2 $1 {The e2-pawn is irrelevant. Byreturning the bishop to the Catalan square White forces the advance of thec-pawn. If 30...Rc8 then the fork 31 Bb7 wins at once.} Ra7 31. c6 {Here thepawn is defended three times and can also be supported by Rac2. There is notalk about it being a target now.} Be7 32. Be4 f6 33. Nf3 Rd8 {EXERCISE: Howdoes White get his knight into the attack again? --- ANSWER:} 34. e3 $1 {Asimple move, but easily overlooked. White