ange. The bishop didn't threaten anything at the time it went to f4, asBlack had the option of ...Rc4. But that is the way it sometimes happens inchess: a move gains strength after the opponent's best reply. In reality Whiteexchanged one threat (13 Qxa7) for another (14 Bb7). And after Black's nextmove - which is again 'best' - we see another chance for White to increase thepressure suddenly appear.} Qb6 {Black meets the threat of 14 Bb7 and puts thequeen on an active square where she ties down the rook on f1 to the defence off2. She also solidifies the queenside in general. On the other hand, thebishop on d7 is left somewhat hanging and Black's kingside is short ofdefenders. --- QUESTION: But the bishop on d7 is defended twice! How is itsomewhat hanging? And where are the white pieces to attack the supposedlyunder-defended black kingside? --- ANSWER: Patience! As after 12 Bf4 we haveto look beyond the present position to see White's chances. Black is going tocastle, after which the bishop on d7 loses one defender, and then White willchallenge its other defender. This will lead to the black kingside becomingdepleted of defenders. Let's see how the game unfolded.} 14. Nd2 O-O 15. Ne4 {Here we are: White threatens to win a piece by capturing on f6.} Nd5 ({Instead,after} 15... Nxe4 16. Bxe4 {both d7 and h7 are hanging.}) ({Or if} 15... Rfd816. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Qf3 {, White can work on the fractured black kingside.Therefore Naiditsch blocks the attack on d7 while preventing damage to hiskingside, but now all Black's minor pieces and his queen are on the queenside.}) 16. Ng5 $5 {Caruana aims to exploit his advantage in firepower on thekingside.} ({In fact} 16. Nxc5 $5 Qxc5 17. Be5 Rfd8 18. Rfd1 {would leave himwith a small but enduring edge because of the bishop pair. Evidently theAmerican Grandmaster preferred to play a more lively game.}) 16... g6 ({Upon} 16... f5 17. Bxd5 {Black can resign as he drops a piece;}) ({while if} 16...Nf6 {the simplest way to win a pawn is} 17. Nxh7 $1 Nxh7 18. Qxd7 {.}) 17. Be5{White continues his kingside build-up.} Be7 ({Naiditsch might have soughtcounterplay against f2 with} 17... f6 18. Bxd5 fxg5 19. Bf3 Bc6 {with unclearplay. Of course it would have been difficult to switch to aggressive play atthe cost of a broken pawn structure when he has played a solid opening so far.}) 18. Nf3 Bc6 19. Qd2 {EXERCISE: Can you see White's threat? And what happensif Black plays 19...Bf6 or 19...Rfd8 to meet it?} f6 {Finally Caruana hasextracted a long-term structural advantage through his positional (we mightsay tactical) pressure on the kingside.} ({ANSWER: The threat was} 19... a6 20.Qh6 f6 (20... Nf6) 21. Ng5 $1 {, when taking the knight allows mate on g7, soto defend h7 Black must give up the exchange with} Rf7 22. Nxf7 {.}) ({If} 19... Bf6 {then} 20. e4 $1 {wins a piece after} Bxe5 21. exd5 {, as both blackbishops hang;}) ({or} 19... Rfd8 20. e4 $1 ({if} 20. Qh6 {Black has} Bf8) 20...Nf6 $2 ({Black has to defend a lousy position with} 20... Nc7 21. Qh6 Ne8 22.Ng5 Bxg5 23. Qxg5 {, though the bishop on e5 dominates the dark squares}) 21.Qg5 $1 Nd5 22. Qh6 Bf8 23. Qh4 Be7 24. Ng5 Bxg5 25. Qxg5 f6 {(if the knightretreats to c7 then 26 Qf6 decides)} 26. Bxf6 Nxf6 27. Qxf6 {and White has wona pawn.}) 20. Bd4 Qb7 ({He prefers not to let the white knight get to a strongcentral post after} 20... Bc5 21. Rac1 Bxd4 22. Nxd4 {.}) 21. Rac1 ({After} 21.Bh3 {,} e5 $5 22. Bxc8 Rxc8 {would be an interesting exchange sacrifice asWhite is weak on the light squares and his bishop passive on e3.}) 21... Rfd822. Bh3 {Aiming the bishop at the undefended pawn.} Bd7 ({If now} 22... e5 23.Bxc8 Rxc8 {, White can take the sting out of Black's sacrifice with} 24. Bc5 $1{.}) 23. Rxc8 Bxc8 ({QUESTION: Why did White give up the c-file and Black notreply} 23... Rxc8 {to take control of it? --- ANSWER: After 23...Rxc8 Whitewould focus on playing on the d-file, either with the immediate} 24. e4 ({ormore likely with} 24. Rd1 {, planning e2-e4 as appropriate (the threat isstronger than the execution!), so Naiditsch keeps his rook on d8 to bolsterhis defences there.})) 24. Rc1 Bd7 25. Bc5 $1 {Black's pawn structure isentrenched on the light squares, but not guarding central dark squares like c5and d4. The exchange of bishops emphasizes Black's fragility whilst vacatingd4 for White's knight or queen.} Bxc5 26. Rxc5 Rc8 {Black is aiming to drawthrough simplification, but there is a favourable way for White to exchangerooks.} 27. b4 $1 {So far Caruana has shown restraint in the use of his footsoldiers, but now is the moment for his pawns to get involved in the struggle.The exchange of rooks will yield him a passed pawn. If Black refuses then 28Nd4 will increase the pressure.} Rxc5 28. bxc5 Qc7 29. e4 $1 {The threat ofthis advance has hung over Black's knight for many moves. Now at last it istime to strike.} Ne7 30. Qd4 $1 {Not only defending the c-pawn, but moreimportantly attacking f6. Black can't reply 30...e5 without dropping hisbishop, and so he has to allow the further advance of White's e-pawn.} Kg7 31.e5 f5 32. Bg2 $1 {The bishop has performed its role on h3 and now returns tog2 to fight for the crucial d5-square.} h6 ({EXERCISE: How should White replyto} 32... Nd5 {, planning 33...Bc6 with a blockade on the light squares? ---ANSWER: An example of Tartakower's dictum that chess is the tragedy of onetempo. Black wants to play ...Nd5, but this fails as he doesn't have theg5-square guarded by a pawn:} 33. Ng5 $1 {(threatening 34 Bxd5)} Qc6 ({Blackhas no time for} 33... Bc6 {as e6 drops}) 34. Kf1 $1 {(why not gain a tempo tocentralize the king rather than take on d5 straightaway?)} h6 35. Bxd5 Qxd5 ({if} 35... exd5 36. e6+ {and wins}) 36. Qxd5 exd5 37. Nf3 Kf7 38. Nd4 {. Whitehas every chance to win: his knight is on a superb blockade square and he hastwo advanced passed pawns which can't be approached by the black king orattacked by the 'bad' bishop.}) 33. Qd6 $1 {An offer to exchange Black can'trefuse.} Qxd6 (33... Nd5 34. Nd4) ({and} 33... Qd8 34. Nd4 {with ideas of 35c6 or 35 Nxe6+ are both fatal for Black.}) 34. exd6 {Only this way: Whitewants two passed pawns and access to e5 for his knight.} Nc6 {Naiditsch'sminor pieces are now blocking the pawns and his king is ready to join in theaction. White has to act fast before Black plays moves like ...Kf6, ...e5-e4, ...Ke6 and ...Kd5 to attack the c5-pawn.} 35. Ne1 $1 ({Also good was} 35. Nd2 $1{, planning Nb3, Bxc6, Na5 and c5-c6 to force the pawns forwards. With thegame move White prepares Nd3 followed by either Bxc6 and then Nb4 and c5-c6 orBxc6 and Ne5 followed by a pawn advance. If Black plays ...Kf6 White can ifnecessary play Bxc6 and then f2-f4! followed by Ne5.}) 35... a5 36. Nd3 b4 {Black has guarded against Nb4, but an approach via e5 is still available tothe white knight.} 37. h4 ({If} 37. Bxc6 Bxc6 38. Ne5 a4 $1 {and Black has thechance to escape, as he should draw after} 39. Nxc6 b3 40. axb3 axb3 41. d7 b242. d8=Q b1=Q+ 43. Kg2 Qe4+ 44. Kf1 Qxc6 {. Caruana therefore prepares to puthis king on h2 so that he would win in this variation as it would no longer becheck when Black promotes.}) 37... Nd4 38. Kh2 $1 ({Steering clear of} 38. Ne5$2 a4 39. Nxd7 b3 {and Black will queen.}) 38... Bb5 ({Or} 38... Kf6 39. f4 Be8{and White is ready for} 40. Ne5 {.}) 39. Ne5 Kf6 40. c6 $1 {A neat finish;} ({though} 40. f4 {also wins.}) 40... Bxc6 ({If now} 40... Kxe5 41. d7 Nxc6 42.Bxc6 {and the pawn gets to d8.}) 41. Nxc6 ({After} 41. Nxc6 Nxc6 42. Bxc6 {,White's bishop will hold back the black queenside pawns whilst defending hispassed pawn on d7. --- A brilliant game by Caruana who showed enormous skilland determination. It's no wonder he was rated 2805 at the time of this game.})1-0[Event "22: Jerusalem"][Site "?"][Date "2015.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Laznicka, V."][Black "Kobo, O."][Result "1-0"][ECO "A05"][An