way tokeep the tension instead of cashing in on the pressure on c6 is} 15. Be4 {:for example,} ({Now after} 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Na5 Rd5 17. Naxc6 bxc6 18. Rxc6Qe8 19. Rdc1 Bd6 20. Qb7 Rd8 {, White's advantage evaporated in M.Andersen-A.Maksimenko, Aarhus 2014.} (20... --)) 15... Qc7 ({or if} 15... g6 {even} 16.Qh3) 16. Qf3 {. The idea of these queen moves is to get off the b3-square inorder to introduce the idea of Na5 without allowing ...Nxa5 in reply. --- Withthe game move Black develops and adds a defender to d4. The drawback is thatthe bishop could itself become a target on c5. With this in mind Whiteresponds by clearing the c1-square for the rook. He chooses f4 for his bishopto support his advanced knight.}) 10. Bf4 ({Alternatively,} 10. Qb3 O-O ({or} 10... Qc8 11. Bf4 O-O 12. Rac1 Nd5 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Bb6 16.Rfd1 Ne7 17. a4 {and White has the initiative}) 11. Bf4 ({if} 11. Qxb7 Nxe5 12.Nxe5 Rb8 13. Qf3 Nd5 {is comfortable for Black}) 11... Rc8 (11... Qc8 12. Rac1Nd5 13. Rfd1 {keeps Black tied up}) 12. Qxb7 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Rb8 14. Qf3 ({Svidler tried} 14. Qxb8 {twice against Naiditsch at Khanty-Mansiysk in 2009,but with little success; after} Qxb8 15. Nxd7 Qb5 16. Nxf8 Bxf8 {, Black'sstrong centre pawns balanced the nominal superiority of having two rooksversus the queen}) 14... Rxb2 15. Rfc1 Bd6 16. Nc4 Bxf4 17. Qxf4 Rb4 18. Qxd4Bb5 19. Qc5 Rxc4 20. Rxc4 Bxc4 21. Qxc4 {. If you play the Catalan you have totry to squeeze out wins with microscopic advantages. In K.Sasikiran-E.Bacrot,Moscow 2010, White tried hard to exploit his superior minor piece, but had toconcede a draw in the end.}) 10... O-O 11. Rc1 {The rook not only makes theblack bishop uneasy, but adds to the pressure on c6.} Nd5 {Blocking the attackon c6, as well as introducing the idea of ...Nxf4. --- EXERCISE: How can Whitekeep on setting Black problems?} ({If now} 11... Nxe5 $2 12. Nxe5 {leaves bothb7 and the bishop on c5 hanging, after which an attempt to create counterplaywith an exchange sacrifice fails utterly:} b6 $2 13. b4 $1 Bxb4 14. Bxa8 Qxa815. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. Qxd4 {and White stands to win.}) ({If instead} 11... Rc8 12.Nd3 Be7 {and now} 13. Nd6 ({perhaps White should keep the tension with} 13. Qd2$5) 13... Rc7 $5 {seems okay for Black.}) 12. Nxd7 {ANSWER: In general Whiteis reluctant to exchange his knight for Black's awkwardly placed bishop, buthere he needs to clear a way for his bishop on f4 to the e5-square. This willinvolve the exchange of both white knights.} ({Besides, there is nothing to begained by} 12. Bxd5 exd5 {If instead in this sequence} 13. Na5 {, uncoveringan attack on c5, then} ({when if} 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. Ne5 Qe7 $1 {, it isdifficult for White to get his pawn back.} ({Note that Black should avoid} 14... Nxe5 $2 15. Bxe5 {, making it easy for the white bishop to attack d4.}))13... Nxa5 14. Rxc5 Bh3 15. Re1 b6 16. Rc1 Rc8 17. Rxc8 ({or} 17. Qxd4 f6 $118. Nd3 {- taking on c8 transposes to the main variation -} Nc6 {and White hasnothing}) 17... Qxc8 18. Qxd4 f6 19. Nd3 Qc4 $1 {and Black is at least okay.})12... Qxd7 13. Ne5 Qd6 $4 {A serious mistake.} ({Instead, after} 13... Nxe5 14.Bxe5 {, Black must save the bishop on c5. After the quiet} Bb6 ({but} 14... Qb5$1 {looks dead equal upon} 15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Bxd4 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Qxe2 18. Rfe1Qa6 19. Qxd5 Rad8 {, etc}) 15. Bxd4 {, White can claim a tiny plus due to thebishop pair.}) 14. Nxc6 Nxf4 15. Na5 $1 {A decisive move. Because the blackknight is hanging on f4 there is no time to deal with the threat of 16 Nxb7.}Nxg2 ({If} 15... b6) ({or} 15... Bb6 {, White wins a piece with} 16. Nc4 {and17 gxf4.}) 16. Nxb7 Qd5 17. Nxc5 {Material is equal, but the black knightwon't be getting out of g2. --- EXERCISE: can you see the best way for Whiteto go about winning the trapped horse?} Rfc8 ({ANSWER: White planned} 17... --18. Qb3 {to crowd out the black queen from the defence of her knight or elseexchange her off.} ({The pretty tactical s