xe4 Bd7 5 Nf3 Bc6. In both cases Black gives priority over developmentto the problem of the bad bishop on c8. However, the two lines aretemperamentally unrelated: in the French Black is looking for a peaceful lifethrough conceding some space, whereas here the aim is to start a hard fight.}6. Ne5 {Sharevich unleashes the bishop and attacks b7, thereby ensuring shegains the bishop pair.} ({EXERCISE: Back in the 1980s Karpov and Kasparov bothfaced this line as White. They settled for} 6. Qc2 {, after which what shouldBlack play? --- ANSWER: One of the good things about 5...Bd7 is that White haslittle choice but to accept the challenge with 6 Ne5. After} c5 $1 7. Qxc4 Bc6{in A.Karpov-G.Sosonko, Wijk aan Zee 1988, and G.Kasparov-V.Korchnoi, 7thmatchgame, London 1983, White had been 'tricked' into a position whichnormally arises after 4...dxc4 5 Qa4+ Bd7 6 Qxc4 c5!. White can't count on anadvantage in this line, as we have seen in Chapter Two.}) 6... Bc6 ({It's toolate for} 6... Nc6 {as after} 7. Nxc4 $1 {Black has a cramped game because theknight on c6 is blocking in the bishop on d7 and also obstructing the freeingadvance ...c7-c5.} ({Note that} 7. Nxd7 {would be a poor reply to 6...Nc6, as}Qxd7 {accelerates Black's plan in the main game}) ({while giving Black tripledpawns with} 7. Nxc6 Bxc6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 {misses the mark. Even if White regainsthe pawn White has been deprived of her king's bishop, leaving her weak on thelight squares. Meanwhile the exchanges have uncluttered Black's position,ensuring an easy development. You might like to compare the damage to Black'squeenside structure with that seen in the Catalan 7 Ne5 mainline. In bothcases Black's activity ensures an acceptable game.})) 7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8. O-O ({Instead,} 8. Qa4 $6 {is in too much of a hurry to get the pawn back: i.e.} Qd79. Qxc4 Nxd4 10. Bxb7 Rb8 11. Bg2 Bb4+ 12. Bd2 O-O $1 {and Black has theinitiative. If now} 13. Bxb4 Rxb4 14. Qxb4 $4 Nc2+ 15. Kf1 {and Black has oneof those