onverted his big endgame advantage as Black andwon on move 51.}) 19. b5 $6 {As so often this proves a naive attacking gesturebecause Black's initiative on the kingside carries a lot more punch.} ({Critical was} 19. Bxd5 {So Black should try} f4 ({when} 19... Bxg3 {, seems tobe a forced draw after} 20. Bxc6 bxc6 21. Qxc6 ({not} 21. fxg3 Qd5 22. Qxc6Rh1+ 23. Kf2 Qxc6 24. Rxc6 Rxa1 {and Black wins the exchange}) 21... Bxf2+ 22.Kxf2 Rh2+ 23. Kf3 Qxc6+ 24. Rxc6 Rxd2 25. Rc5 f4 {, leading to a drawn rookand pawn endgame.}) 20. Bxc6 bxc6 21. exf4 gxf4 22. Qxc6 fxg3 23. Qxd7 Rxd7 24.f4 Rh2 25. Be3 Re7 {. Despite being a pawn down, Black retains a stronginitiative in the endgame thanks to his active rooks, the strong passed pawnon g3 and the awkward position of the white king.}) 19... Ne7 {Such is thepower of Black's looming attack that she might already be adjudged to have awinning position.} 20. f4 {A radical way to stop the ...f5-f4-pawn thrust.} Ng8$1 {The knight moves out of the way of the queen to allow her to go to h7 tolead the attack down the h-file. At the same time the horse heads for e4, amarvellous outpost in the centre created by White's previous move.} 21. Qb3 ({After} 21. Bxd5 Nf6 22. Bg2 gxf4 23. exf4 Rdg8 24. Be1 Ne4 {Black's piecesexert intolerable pressure on the white kingside.}) 21... Nf6 22. fxg5 {Seeingno long-term answer to her opponent's build-up Sharevich tries tocounterattack which leads to a speedy collapse.} Ne4 {The knight finds acommanding square after a journey from b8 via c6, e7, g8 and f6.} 23. Be1 Qh724. Qxd5 Bxg3 25. Qe6 Nxg5 {Now the horse removes the last pawn barrier on thekingside.} 26. Qc4 Bxe1 27. Rxe1 Ne4 28. Qc2 Rdg8 29. Rac1 Qh1# 0-1[Event "24: Jerusalem"][Site "?"][Date "2016.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Veinberg, N."][Black "Baron, T."][Result "0-1"][ECO "E04"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "64"][EventDate "2016.??.??"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2