RCISE: Can you work out which of 13...Bb7, 13...Rb8 or 13...e5 is thebest move for Black? --- ANSWER:} e5 $1 {Chess strategy is not only aboutputting your pieces on good squares - that is, making them work harder. Youalso need to think about how to undo the work of the opponent's pieces.} ({Ifhere} 13... Rb8 {then} 14. Qe5 $1 {follows and the white queen gets to sit ona good centre square where she incidentally attacks the rook on b8. If then}Bb7 {White could continue} 15. Nc3 {and 16 Bg5, when Black's compensation forthe pawn is fast fading. When you see how the white queen is pushed around byHou Yifan in the game you'll realize you don't want her sitting with impunityon e5.}) ({The other possibility is} 13... Bb7 {. The bishop is, indeed, wellplaced on b7, but the rook on a8 is annoyed that it is deprived of its openfile. Because there is no pressure on b2 White can play} 14. Bg5 {at once andanswer} Rfd8 {with} 15. Qh4 {. Again Black's compensation for the pawn isvanishing. --- In the game after 13...e5, the white queen is chased from thecentre. Black gets her rook on to the open file and also plays ...Bb7 withoutthe pieces obstructing each other. Furthermore, the e6-square proves usefulfor the black queen not only to break a pin after Bg5, but also as an avenueof attack on the white king via the light squares. And to add to all thesegoodies, in the game the e5-pawn will prove a battering ram against the whitekingside.}) 14. Qh4 Rb8 {The white queen is dislodged and the black rook eyesthe b2-pawn.} 15. b3 ({After} 15. Nc3 {Black had better do something fast orelse 16 Bg5 is good for White. The vigorous response} Rb4 16. e4 h6 {is calledfor. The pin is prevented and White's queen finds herself stalemated.}) ({If} 15. Bg5 Rxb2 {. Perhaps White should play like this anyway, to be equal after}16. Nc3 Qe6 17. e4 {.}) 15... Qe6 ({Note that} 15... Rb4 {would fail to} 16.Ba3 $1 {and Black loses material. Hou Yifan therefore breaks the pin on herknight and brings her queen on to a light square as a prelude to an assault onthe kingside.}) 16. Na3 ({If} 16. Bg5 Nd5 {, etc.}) 16... Rd8 17. Qc4 Qh3 {Thethreat of 18...Ng4 forces White to weaken his king's defences.} 18. f3 Bb7 19.Qc2 $6 {After this Black will get a fearsome initiative, even if objectivelyspeaking White can still defend.} ({White had to reduce the potential pressureon his kingside, either with} 19. Bg5 {to eliminate the black knight;}) ({orwith} 19. e4 {, which would prevent Black's next move.}) 19... e4 $1 {Usingthe f3-pawn as a lever for opening up the long diagonal. Black has bags ofplay for a mere pawn.} 20. Nc4 Rbc8 21. Rf2 Qh5 {EXERCISE: Try to work out ifit is better for White to play 22 Bb2 or 22 Be3.} 22. Be3 $2 ({ANSWER: Whitehad to play} 22. Bb2 $1 {in order to eliminate the f6-knight before it canland on the g4-square giving Black a decisive initiative.} {Instead, Blackcould try} Ba6 $5 {to keep up the initiative and reserve the threat ofinvading with ...Rd2. This would leave White with a badly placed rook on g2.--- It would require a cool head to play 22 Bb2 and not fear 22...Rd2, but Icould imagine a great defender like Capablanca seeing through the position andconcluding 'My main enemy is the knight, I must get rid of it at all costs'.--- After the game move White's defences crumble. There is no defence againstthe fearsome light-squared bishop.} ({Naturally Wang Hao was loathe to allowthe black rook to penetrate after} 22... e3 23. Rg2 Rd2 {, but in fact after}24. Qc3 Rxe2 {(which looks crushing), White can hold on by defending f3 with}25. Rf1 {. If then} ({it is mate in two upon} 25. Rxe2 Qxf3 {, as with} 26.Qxe3 Qh1+ 27. Kf2 Ng4#) 25... Bxf3 $2 {White can turn the tables with} 26. Rxe2Bxe2 27. Rxf6 $1 gxf6 28. Qxf6 {with a winning attack. Incidentally, this linedemonstrates the influence of opposite-coloured bishops on scenarios where aking is vulnerable. If Hou Yifan relinquishes the initiative then it is