2. --- In the present game, however, with the queen on a4,} 12. Rd1 $2 exd4{would just be bad for White. Therefore the e-pawn central break becomes moreattractive for Black.}) ({At the same time} 11... c5 {has become lessappealing than in the game above.} {Alternatively,} 12. Qc6 {wins the c5-pawnbecause of the threat to a8: for example,} ({Rather than transpose with WangHao's} 12. Qxc4 {, White has extra options due to the more flexible positionof the white queen on a4.}) ({Firstly,} 12. Qa3 {pins the c5-pawn. Then, forexample,} Qb7 13. Qxc5 e5 14. Rd1 Bh3 15. d5 {keeps an edge for White.} (15. --)) 12... Bb7 13. Qxc5 Qxc5 {(usual)} ({keeping the queens on with} 13... Qd7 $5{might be a better approach}) 14. dxc5 Rfc8 15. Be3 Ng4 16. Bd4 e5 17. Bc3 Rxc518. Rd1 {followed by Na3 and again White has the better chances.}) 12. dxe5Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {QUESTION: After the game move not only is Black down a pawn, healso has broken queenside pawns. If everything else were equal, this wouldsurely be more than enough for an arch-strategist like Kramnik to bag thepoint as White. So what is Black's compensation?} ({After} 13. Nc3 $5 Ne4 $514. Qxc4 Nxc3 15. bxc3 ({not} 15. Qxc3 Qxe2) 15... Be6 16. Qd3 Rad8 17. Bf4 Qc518. Qc2 Qc6 {, Black's light-square superiority means that any attempt atexploiting his extra pawn by White with an eventual f2-f3 and e2-e4 advancewould leave him fragile. For example, if} 19. f3 Bh3 20. Rfd1 $2 ({instead} 20.Rf2 {is required, but awkward for the rook}) 20... Qc5+ {, when} 21. Kh1 (21.e3 {White loses a piece upon} g5) 21... Qf2 22. Rg1 Rfe8 23. Rae1 {(otherwisee2 drops)} Bg2+ $1 24. Rxg2 Qxe1+ {wins for Black.}) 13... Be6 {ANSWER: It isimperative for Black that he gains time by hitting the white queen. Not onlythe bishop, but also the black rooks can be mobilized with gain of time byharassing her. She is obliged to defend the e2-pawn and shouldn't wander toofar from the kingside as her assistance is needed in thwarting any attack ledby the black queen. This explains her tortuous manoeuvres. On the other hand,the prize is worth a lot of suffering. If White can escape the pressure thenhe has enough material advantage to win the game.} ({If Black settled for} 13... Bb7 {, then the bishop looks pretty on the long diagonal, but White candevelop with} 14. Nc3 {and play f2-f3 if the black queen made threateningnoises with ...Qh5. With the bishop coming out to f4 White would be in command.}) ({Likewise, if} 13... Bh3 14. Re1 {(it's kind of Black to drive the whiterook to e1 where it defends e2 and frees the queen of the task) leaves Whitefree to develop.}) 14. Qd3 ({White's queen is also pushed about after} 14. Qc2{: for example,} Bf5 15. Qd2 Bh3 16. Re1 Rad8 17. Qe3 Qd5 18. f3 Ng4 19. Qc3 {Instead,} Rfe8 {sets up a brilliant trap:} ({and here} 19... Qb7 20. Bf4 {wasdraw agreed in Wen Yang-P.Leko, Baku 2015, but White looks a bit better.} (20.--)) {White should therefore develop with} 20. Na3 {, when Black has enoughcounterplay for the material, but no more than that after} ({namely} 20. Bf4 $2Rxe2 $3 21. Rxe2 Qc5+ $1 {(the point: White is mated if he takes the queen)}22. Be3 Rd1+ 23. Re1 Rxe1+ 24. Qxe1 Nxe3 25. Kh1 {(getting away from thediscovered attack)} ({if} 25. Qf2 Qc1+ {will mate}) 25... Nc2 26. Qe8+ Qf8 {and after all his attacking moves, Black wins in prosaic style by taking therook on a1.}) 20... Qb7 21. Bf4 Qb6+ 22. e3 Qb7 23. e4 Qb6+ 24. Be3 Nxe3 25.Rxe3 Be6 26. Kg2 Rd4 27. Re2 Red8 {, etc}) 14... Rad8 15. Qe3 Qh5 {Of course,the exchange of queens is anathema for Black. Now White meets the threat of 16...Ng4, which would win at once, and creates a hideaway for his queen on f2.} ({Meanwhile, if instead} 15... Qa5 16. Qa3 {(getting the queen out of the way ofpotential attacks after Rfe8)} Qh5 17. Nc3 {and White has some edge.}) 16. f3Bc4 {Black wastes no time in aiming at e2, the weakest square in White'scentre.} ({After} 16... Rfe8 {White has the chance to play