d 23 Nxg6+White will end up with an extra rook.}) 21. Re1 h5 22. g5 f6 $2 ({EXERCISE:Can you make 22...Bxe2 work for Black? --- ANSWER: Indeed, the e2-pawn is nolonger poisoned, so Black misses a tactical chance to equalize with} 22... Bxe2$1 23. Rxe2 Rd1+ 24. Kg2 Rxe2 25. Qxe2 Rxc1 $1 {(the point, setting up a forkon g5)} 26. Rxc1 Qxg5+ {and 27...Qxc1.}) 23. h4 Rde5 24. e4 f5 25. Bf4 R5e7 26.Rac1 {A blitz game inaccuracy.} ({White could keep a solid queenside structurewith} 26. b3 {and, after} Bf7 {, close the centre with} 27. e5 {. He wouldthen be well on top.}) 26... Bxa2 27. Qxa7 Bf7 28. Rxc7 ({Again} 28. e5 {wasthe right idea. It would concede the d5-square to Black's bishop, but hisrooks remain boxed in.}) 28... Rxc7 29. Qxc7 fxe4 30. Rxe4 Rxe4 31. fxe4 Qxe4 {Black has broken out and has enough for a draw due to the exposed white king.}32. Qe5 Qf3 33. Bg3 $4 {Don't judge Kramnik on this howler played in a blitzgame.} ({Instead, White could draw easily with} 33. Qe3 {which prevents Blackfrom setting up a deadly queen and bishop battery against his king.}) 33... Bd5{Suddenly there is no good way to stop mate on g2.} 34. Qe8+ Kh7 35. g6+ Kh636. Qh8+ Kxg6 37. Qe8+ Kh7 {. White's attempt at a perpetual has fizzled out.}0-1[Event "29: Saint Louis"][Site "?"][Date "2016.??.??"][Round "?"][White "So, W."][Black "Nakamura, H."][Result "1-0"][ECO "E05"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "75"][EventDate "2016.??.??"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2017.08.07"]1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8.Nxc6 ({In contrast to the} 8. Bxc6 {variation above, here White doesn't emergewith an extra pawn from the opening. On the other hand, he keeps his Catalanbishop so isn't afflicted by the light-square malaise of the previous games inthis chapter.}) 8... bxc6 {EXERCISE: Black's queenside pawn structure is nowwrecked, with tripled pawns along the c-file. Assuming he hasn't gone mad, canyou think of some reasons why Nakamura would let his opponent smash up hisqueenside?} 9. Na3 $5 ({ANSWER: Consider the position after} 9. Bxc6 Rb8 {.First of all it just looks horrible for Black. But notice that his rook on a8is on an open line, putting pressure on b2 and tying down the bishop on c1 toits defence. How often in the Catalan do we see this rook get so active soquickly? Secondly, White's bishop is loosely placed on c6. Black could forceits exchange with a quick ...Bb7, thereby solving the problem of the badbishop on c8. --- Once the light-squared bishops are exchanged, Black can dosomething to improve his queenside pawn structure: namely arrange the ...c7-c5advance and liquidate by exchange White's d4-pawn. Black will have achieved alot: he is rid of his bad bishop, has an active rook on b8 and can dissolveWhite's pawn centre. Of course, he would remain with split queenside pawns,and a rather vulnerable pawn on c4, but you can't have everything. Black lookscomfortable. --- Let's see an example of how things might unfold:} 10. Nc3 Bb711. Bxb7 Rxb7 12. e4 c5 13. dxc5 ({we see another use of the rook on b7 after} 13. d5 Rd7 $1 {winning the d5-pawn}) 13... Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Bxc5 15. Kg2 {and nowBlack found a nice move:} e5 $1 {, securing the d4-square for his bishop whereit adds to the pressure on b2 and blocks under counterplay along the d-file.After} 16. Rd2 Bd4 17. Rc2 Rfb8 {, Black had a good game in M.Elgabry-M.Kravtsiv, Al Ain 2012.}) ({Another try for White is} 9. Qa4 {, but} Qxd4 {(acentre pawn is worth a little trouble as Steinitz would say!)} 10. Rd1 Qb6 11.Be3 Qa6 (11... Qxb2 $5 {was also worth the trouble, with good chances for Black}) 12. Qxc6 Qxc6 13. Bxc6 Rb8 14. Bxa7 Rxb2 {and Black's activity gave him thebetter game in Vo Thanh Ninh-Nguyen Ngoc Truong Son, Ho Chi Minh City 2016.}) ({Alternatively, White could defend his d-pawn with} 9. e3 {to free his queenfor action:} Ba6 10. Bxc6 Rb8 11. Nc3 ({If} 11. Qa4 Rb6 {holds everythingtogether for Black}) 11... Nd5 $1 12. Nxd5 {(this straightens out Black'spawns, but otherwise the bishop on c6 is stranded)} exd5 13. Qf3 Bb7 {(defending d5)} ({notice that} 13... c3 {wins the exchange after} 14. bxc3 Bxf1{, but after} 15. Kxf1 {the d5-pawn will drop leaving White with enoughmaterial and a strong centre}) 14. Bxb7 Rxb7 15. b3 {and now} c3 $5 {was thedynamic try; for example,} ({rather than} 15... cxb3 {in V.Ivanchuk-Y.Seirawan,Tilburg 1992}) 16. e4 dxe4 17. Qxe4 c6 $1 {(a cute way to get the rook to c7to defend c3; if White refuses the pawn then 18...Qd5 centralizes the queenstrongly)} 18. Qxc6 Rc7 19. Qe4 Bd6 20. Bf4 Re8 21. Qf3 c2 {and Black'sdangerous passed pawn supplies strong counterplay for the material.}) 9... Bxa3{QUESTION: Why does Black give up his excellent dark-squared bishop? ---ANSWER: In some positions even a powerful bishop has to be exchanged for agalloping horse. If White is allowed to play 10 Nxc4 unopposed the knightcould then go to e5 or a5 to conquer c6. White would have a crushing game.} ({For example,} 9... Rb8 10. Nxc4 c5 11. Na5 Bd7 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Nb7 Qe7 14.Nxc5 Qxc5 15. Be3 {leaves White with the two bishops and split pawns to targeton a7 and c7.}) ({Also} 9... Ba6 {doesn't help much as, after} 10. Qa4 Qc8 11.Nxc4 {, Black is in deep trouble due to the weakness on c6. Instead, withthe game move Black inflicts doubled pawns on White and turns the c4-pawn intoa passed pawn.}) 10. bxa3 Ba6 {Black develops his bishop to an active squareand defends the pawn that matters - the passed pawn. He doesn't have to worryabout jettisoning the c6-pawn as after 11 Bxc6 Rb8 he will generate a lot ofplay with ...Nd5, etc, in the style of the Seirawan and Kravtsiv extractsabove. --- EXERCISE: After 10...Ba6 what is White's best way to get his queeninto the attack?} ({If instead} 10... Rb8 {, White has the chance to get ridof Black's advanced passed pawn with} 11. Qa4 Qxd4 12. Be3 Qe5 