s king can only watchevents from a distance.} Nf6 22. Kf1 $1 {A vital move in White's plans. Blackcan only mark time with his king, whereas the white monarch edges over to c1.}Kh7 23. Qc2+ Kg8 24. Qd2 Kh7 25. Qd8 Qxd8 26. Rxd8 c3 27. Ke1 {Just in time tohead off the c-pawn. There is a well-known rule that if you are the exchangeup in an endgame, you should try to exchange off the opponent's remaining rook.Here we see that once the passed pawns are neutralized the black minor piecesare no match for the wide ranging white rook.} Bc4 28. Kd1 Bxa2 29. Kc2 Bc4 30.e3 {The c3 pawn is doomed - there's no need to give Black the e2-pawn.} b5 31.Kxc3 a6 32. Ra8 Nd5+ 33. Bxd5 exd5 34. a5 $1 {Fixing the a6-pawn as a targetand maintaining a potential outside passed pawn.} b4+ 35. Kd2 Bf1 {EXERCISE:What is the correct technique to decide the game? --- ANSWER:} 36. Rc8 $1 {Thepassed pawns have to be forced on to light squares where they can be totallyblocked by the white king.} c4 37. Rb8 b3 38. Kc3 ({After} 38. Kc3 Bd3 39. Rd8({White has to avoid being swindled with} 39. Rb6 g6 40. Rxa6 $2 b2 $1 41. Kxb2$2 c3+ {, when he loses his rook and possibly the game}) 39... Be4 40. Rd6 Bd341. Rxd5 {, White wins easily;} ({or else} 41. Rxa6 {wins})) 1-0[Event "30: Luxembourg"][Site "?"][Date "2016.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Kelires, A."][Black "Villegas, P."][Result "1-0"][ECO "E06"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "55"][EventDate "2016.??.??"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2017.08.07"]1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5 c5 ({Black avoids the damage to his queenside pawns that would occur after} 7... Nc6{. Ignoring the white knight he strikes at d4, a plan which is all the moreattractive as the white pawn has lost one of its defenders after 7 Ne5. Onceit is liquidated, there will be an almost symmetrical pawn structure. Surelyit can't be that difficult for Black to neutralize White's pressure and offera draw? --- As we know it is never that easy for Black in the Catalan. IfBlack achieves the ...c7-c5 advance in the Queen's Gambit without incurringany weaknesses or danger to his king, he often equalizes. However, the whitebishop being on g2, rather than d3 or e2 as it would be in the Queen's Gambit,makes a huge difference. The bishop points inexorably at b7, so that even ifthe freeing advance ...c7-c5 is carried out, Black remains with problemsdeveloping his bishop from c8. White is usually pleased to see Black's'freeing' advance ...c7-c5 in the Catalan. --- Strong players often flounderin slightly worse positions where they have no constructive plan. Generallyspeaking, players love to have something to do. If there is nothing good to dothey'll find something bad. Perhaps that is the secret of the Catalan.}) ({Also after} 7... Nbd7 8. Nxc4 c5 9. dxc5 Bxc5 ({or} 9... Nxc5 10. Nc3) 10. Nc3Nb6 11. Nxb6 Bxb6 12. Bf4 {, White's pressure on b7 won't go away.}) 8. dxc5Qc7 ({The exchange of queens doesn't help Black:} 8... Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bxc5 10.Nc3 Nc6 11. Nxc4 {, when he can't shake off the bind;}) ({or} 8... Bxc5 9. Qxd8Rxd8 10. Nc3 Nc6 {(an attempt to break free by returning a pawn on c6 ratherthan allowing a recapture on c4)} 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bxc6 Rb8 13. Bf4 Rb4 ({not} 13... Rxb2 14. Na4 {with a winning fork}) 14. Rfd1 Rf8 15. Na4 {. Black isdisorganized, passive and with a weakness on c4.}) 9. Nxc4 Qxc5 {EXERCISE: Howcan White meet the threat to the knight whilst also continuing to build up thepressure? --- ANSWER:} 10. b3 $1 Rd8 ({If now} 10... Nc6 11. Ba3 Qh5 12. Bxe7Nxe7 13. Nc3 {and White's queen controls the d-file. Furthermore, the exchangeof dark-squared bishops has weakened Black's hold on d6 - imagine the havoc ifWhite managed to land a knight or his queen on that square after suitablepreparation.}) 11. Nbd2 Qc7 {The queen goes back to help defend the queenside.Black is almost equal, but in the Catalan there is a big difference between'almost equal' and completely equal.} ({QUESTION: After} 11... Qh5 $6 {, is 12e4 or 12 e3 a better way for White to offer the exchange of queens? --- ANSWER:Both pawn moves seem good for White:} {However, I think} 12. e3 {is a betterway to start: White reserves the option of moving the pawn to e4 and meanwhilegives his opponent the chance to go wrong. For example,} ({More aggressive is} 12. e4 {as it controls space and gives White an edge after} Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Nc614. e5 Nd5 15. Ne4 {.} (15. --)) 12... Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Nd5 ({one such way to gowrong is} 13... Nc6 $2 {, when} 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Na5 Bd7 16. Ndc4 Be8 17. Ba3Bxa3 18. Nxa3 {leaves Black with a horrible weakness on c6}) 14. Bb2 Nc6 15.Nf3 Bd7 16. e4 {(only now)} Nf6 17. Nfe5 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Bb5 ({similar is} 18...Be8 19. Bd6 Bxd6 20. Nxd6 Bc6 21. e5) 19. Bd6 $1 {(clearing the way to advancethe e-pawn when the bishop on g2 comes alive)} Bf8 20. e5 {and Black'sposition is creaking. --- There is no need to hurry to clarify an advantagewhen the opponent is in a bind.}) 12. Bb2 Nc6 13. Rc1 Bd7 14. e3 $1 {At themoment both queens are uncomfortable as they stand on the same file as anenemy rook, but White is able to create an excellent central post on e2 forhis queen. Meanwhile his opposite number slinks away on to the back rank onthe queenside.} Rac8 15. Qe2 Be8 16. Rfd1 Qb8 17. Nf3 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Rd8 19.Rc1 $6 ({Instead,} 19. Nfe5 {is a small advantage for White. Understandably hewishes to avoid the exchange of rooks as he has more space.}) 19... Nd5 $6 ({Black could have achieved counterplay with} 19... Nb4 {, attacking the a2-pawnand with ideas of ...Nd3. After} 20. Be5 {, the natural reply} Qa8 {buries theblack queen and is good for White.} ({However, the 'computer' move} 20... Qc8$1 {, putting the queen opposite the white rook and threatening 21...b5, issuddenly a good idea for Black. Naturally a human player is unlikely to lookbeyond 19...Nb4 20 Be5 and think 20.