on material at once: f6 can't be held as} Ng8 27.exf6+ Nxf6 28. Qg5+ {costs Black a piece.}) 26. e5 $1 {White wins theg5-square for his queen and e5 for his knight, which makes the rook on d8 andthe pawn on f7 into tactical targets.} fxe5 27. Qg5+ Kf8 28. Nxe5 ({If} 28.Nxe5 Qc7 (28... Bxg2 29. Qf6 {decides at once as Black has no good way todefend to defend f7 with his queen}) 29. Qf6 {threatens 30 Nxf7!, when 30...Qxf7 would drop the rook on d8. White has a decisive attack: for example,} Rd630. Qh8+ Ke7 31. Qxh7 {with fatal pressure on f7.}) 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "8: Main Line: 7 Qc2 b6 & 7..b5"][Black "?"][Result "*"][ECO "E05"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "14"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2017.08.07"]{In this chapter we'll look at two ways for Black to avoid the Catalanmainline after} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc47. Qc2 ({A refinement to avoid the 7 Qc2 b5 line is} 7. Qa4 $5 {, when Blackwill almost certainly continue} a6 {, after which} ({meanwhile, for a note on} 7... b6 {see Game 32}) 8. Qxc4 {reaches positions examined in Chapter Ten.})7... a6 {.} ({These are} 7... b6) ({and} 7... b5 {.}) *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "The Bukavshin Variation"][Black "?"][Result "*"][ECO "E05"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "17"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2017.08.07"]1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 {. IvanBukavshin was an enormous chess talent from Russia. He died from a stroke in2016 at the tragically young age of 20. His rating was already 2658, and hisgames were full of interesting concepts. One of these was} b6 $5 {in theCatalan, which he championed versus Artemiev and Leko and others withoutsuffering any defeats. It is certainly an intriguing idea. --- Trying for anoutright refutation with} 8. 