ated, Black is slightly loose on the light squares: this means the whiteknight finds a good post on the c4-square, from which it can no longer bedriven by a black pawn on the b-file or on the d-file. Nor has Black solvedthe perennial problem of the backward pawn on c7.} ({Instead,} 9. Qxc4 Ba6 10.Qc2 Nbd7 {is already fine for Black. If then} 11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. Bxa8 ({if} 12.dxe5 Nd5) 12... Qxd4 13. Bg2 c5 {gives Black a strong initiative for theexchange due to his mass of queenside pawns and pressure on e2.}) ({Black'squeenside pawns are also irritating for White upon} 9. Bg5 Ba6 10. Nbd2 b3 11.Qc1 Nc6 12. Nxc4 Rc8 13. Rd1 Nb4 {. The attempt to round up the b3 pawn leftWhite worse after} 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Qc3 Nc2 16. Rac1 c5 17. Qxb3 Nxd4 {in P.Bjarnehag-R.Stern, Berlin 2012.}) ({White can play more sharply with 9 Ne5 or9 Nfd2 uncovering an attack on a8: After} 9. Ne5 Qxd4 $1 {, it is bad forWhite to take on a8:} {After} 10. Nxc4 (10. Bxa8 $2 Qxe5 11. Bf4 ({after} 11.Bf3 Ba6 12. Bf4 Qa5 13. Nd2 b3 14. Qc1 Qb4 {, Black has a strong initiativefor the exchange with active pieces and threatening queenside pawns}) 11... Qh512. Bf3 Ng4 13. Bxg4 ({or if} 13. h4 e5 {with an attack}) 13... Qxg4 {ispromising for Black as White misses his light-squared bishop}) ({Instead,} 10.Nd2 {is a tricky move: it is best answered by} Qxe5 {when} 11. Nxc4 ({not} 11.Bxa8 Qxe2) 11... Qh5 12. Bxa8 c6 {is unclear. White is the exchange up, buthis bishop is awkwardly placed on a8.}) {but he has an extra option of} 10...Nd5 {: for example,} ({Black could transpose with} 10... c6 {to 9 Nfd2 c6 10Nxc4 as discussed below;} 11. -- (11. --)) 11. Be3 ({if} 11. e4 Nb6 {looksgood for Black}) 11... Qf6 ({or maybe} 11... Qg4) 12. Nbd2 {. White's pressureis balanced by the extra black pawn.}) (9. Nfd2 {looks a more precise moveorder, but again Black seems okay after} c6 10. Nxc4 ({White should avoid} 10.e3 b3 $1 11. Qd1 Ba6 {, holding on to the c4-pawn}) 10... Qxd4 11. Rd1 Qc5 {Or}12