White has spent a tempo on the wing move 8 a4 andneglected to control the c5-square with 8 Qxc4, so the freeing thrust ...c7-c5is both natural and logical. --- Indeed, in any Queen's Pawn Opening theadvance ...c7-c5 deserves attention, both from White who should considerwhether to allow it, and Black who should check if he can carry it out withoutbeing punished. It might be said that the freeing move ...c7-c5 is on thewhole less assuring of a safe game for Black in the Catalan than in theQueen's Gambit. The pressure from the bishop on g2 doesn't go away. --- Herethe drawback is that Black has to move his bishop from e7 to recapture hispawn, losing time and leaving his kingside slightly under protected. He isalso opening up the c- and d-files which is always a little dangerous if theopponent's rooks are going to arrive first at the scene. --- Nonetheless, itis by no means easy for White to keep an edge after 8...c5.}) 9. dxc5 Bxc5 ({Black doesn't want to be saddled with broken pawns after} 9... Nbd7 10. c6 $1 {(a typical example of a desperado move)} bxc6 11. Qxc4 {.}) 10. Qxc4 ({Instead} 10. Nbd2 {aims to regain the pawn in a superior manner by bringing theknight to c4.} {Black can avoid the (often fatal) little disadvantage with thedynamic} b5 $5 {. Black plays the 'impossible' move as a gambit in order toactivate his bishop on b7. After} ({After} 10... Nc6 11. Nxc4 Qe7 12. Nfe5 {,we have the supposedly 'small' edge for White that has led to countlessdefeats for Black in similar Catalan scenarios. It's hardly ever good news forBlack to have the bishop stuck on c8 when the centre is open.} (12. --)) 11.axb5 Bb7 12. bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qxc4 Bd5 14. Qh4 Be7 {Black is a pawn down, but hispieces are very well coordinated in contrast to White's scattered army. A drawwas agreed after} 15. Qf4 Bd6 16. Qh4 Be7 17. Qf4 Bd6 18. Qh4 {in A.Donchenko-I.Lysyj, Warsaw 2016.} (18. --)) 10... Qe7 $6 {Black defends thebishop and evacuates the queen from d8 where she might be a target for afuture Rd1. He also keeps the option of using his b-pawn actively. Nonethelessthe queen isn't entirely happy on e7 because of a possible Bg5 pin in thefuture.} ({Instead,} 10... b6 $5 {is a tough nut to crack. It has been used inblitz games by Topalov and Kramnik. Then} 11. Nc3 ({after} 11. Ne5 Ra7 {Blackgets in ...Bb7 quickly}) 11... Bb7 12. Bg5 Nbd7 {also looks very solid forBlack, though White can probe with} 13. Rfd1 Qc8 {(threatening to win thewhite queen!)} 14. Qf4 {intending Rac1, etc}) 11. Nc3 b5 12. Qh4 b4 $6 {Helping White build up his initiative. --- EXERCISE: We don't often get toattack the king in the Catalan, so let's try to get it right. What is thestrongest attacking move?} ({If you have looked at the notes to 10 Qxc4 youmight be inspired to make the pawn sacrifice} 12... Bb7 $1 {. As in the Lysyjgame it would be very difficult for White to make progress upon} 13. axb5 axb514. Rxa8 Bxa8 15. Nxb5 Nbd7 16. Nc3 Rb8 {as his pieces are ineffectivecompared to the Black's well-organized forces.}) 13. Ng5 $1 {ANSWER: Now therook on a8 is en prise.} ({Much better than} 13. Ne4 {, when} Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Bb7{is just fine for Black.}) 13... Bb7 14. Nce4 {White has a fearsome attackwith the threat of mate in two. Black dare not exchange on e4 as 14...Bxe4 15Bxe4 leaves both a8 and h7 hanging. The upshot is that White is able toeliminate the defender of the black queen with his next move and so win a pawn.} Nbd7 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 ({Hopeless for Black is} 15... Bxg2 16. Nxd7 {.}) 16. Nxh7$1 Bxg2 {EXERCISE: Which of these options is the best way for White tocontinue? (a) Pin the black knight with 17 Bg5; (b) Recapture his piece with17 Kxg2; (c) Exchange with 17 Nxf6+ then recapture on g2. --- ANSWER:} 17. Bg5$1 {The correct approach is to keep up the attack on the kingside.} ({Tooinsipid is} 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Qxf6 gxf6 19. Kxg2 Nb3 {and Black hassignificant counterplay in the endgame: we might continue} 20. Rb1 Rfd8 21. Be3Rac8 {and the rook will invade with 22...Rc2.}) ({The other problem for Whiteis that he loses a piece after} 17. Kxg2 $2 Qb7+ {and 18...Nxh7.}) ({Thereforewith} 17. Bg5 {he threatens} -- 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. Bxf6 {, when Black mustpart with his queen to stop mate on h8. This forces Black to add a defender tof6, either with his actual move or 17...Nbd7. In either case White can thensafely recapture on g2 as the unpinning move ...Qb7+ is no longer available toBlack. Thus White achieves his aim of avoiding simplification.}) 17... Nce4 {The best way to defend f6 as it allows an exchange on g5 to ease the pressure.}18. Kxg2 Nxg5 19. Nxg5 Rfd8 20. Rfd1 Qc5 {It looks at first glance as if Blackhas avoided the worst. He is a pawn down, but the white queen and knight are'offside' whereas his own queen can terrorize White's queenside with ...Qc2.However with his next couple of moves Damljanovic shows that his kingsideattack is still alive and well.} 21. e4 $1 {All the better for being delayedfor 21 moves. Hardly any attack can succeed without the help of pawns. Itisn't enough to push the big pieces around and expect the opponent's defencesto cave in: they have to be undermined by pawns. --- EXERCISE: Can you see aclever way for White to simplify the position if given the chance?} ({ANSWER:After} 21. e4 {, White intends} -- 22. e5 Qxe5 23. Qh8+ $1 Kxh8 24. Nxf7+ Kg825. Nxe5 {, when he remains a pawn up in the endgame having weakened Black'skingside to boot.}) 21... Rxd1 22. Rxd1 Qc2 {Still trying to distract Whitefrom his initiative by widening the struggle.} 23. Re1 $1 e5 ({Black must stop} 23... -- 24. e5 {when, after} Nd5 {,} 25. Re4 $1 {is a key move which blocksthe black queen's defence of the h7-square so that 26 Qh7+ becomes a lethalthreat.}) 24. Re3 $1 {Gambiting the b2-pawn to gain a decisive attack.} Qxb2 {QUESTION: It looks like Black has serious counterplay with his passed pawn,doesn't he? --- ANSWER: There is a move that gives vital energy to White'sattack. The b-pawn won't matter.} 25. g4 {The game move clears the way for therook to combine its power with the queen on the h-file.} ({Perhaps Black onlyreckoned with} 25. Rf3 -- ({but} 25... Ra7 $1 {fights on by defending thef7-square}) {, which threatens} 26. Rxf6 gxf6 27. Qh7+ Kf8 28. Qxf7# {.}) 25...Qc2 26. Rh3 Kf8 27. Qh8+ Ng8 28. Rh7 {Now there is no way to defend g7 as 28...g6 allows mate in two moves.} Ke7 29. Qxg7 {. With the f7- and e5-pawns bothhanging, Black has no time to utilize the b-pawn before his king is butchered.}1-0[Event "35: Saint Louis"][Site "?"][Date "2015.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Nakamura, H."][Black "Anand, V."][Result "1-0"][ECO "E06"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "85"][EventDate "2015.??.??"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2017.08.07"]1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4Bd7 {The main move. The bishop heads for the long diagonal to challenge itscounterpart on g2.} 9. Qxc4 Bc6 {Mission accomplished. --- EXERCISE: Beforereading further, can you see any drawbacks for Black to having his bishop onc6?} ({In contrast to the 7 Qc2 a6 8 Qxc4 b5 line, here} 9... b5 {doesn't makemuch sense when there is no bishop to go to b7. After} 10. Qc2 bxa4 $6 11. Ne5Nd5 12. Nc3 {, White will quickly regain the pawn with Nxa4, leaving Blackwith weaknesses.}) 10. Bg5 {ANSWER: Here are some possible minus points to thebishop being on c6: a) It blocks the c7-pawn, thus ruling out a quick freeing ...c7-c5 advance. --- b) The bishop takes away the c6-square from the knight onb8. --- c) If White arranges e2-e4 then Ne5 could be strong for him as theexchange with ...Bxg2 won't be possible in reply.} ({The alternative} 10. Bf4 {is the subject of the next game.}) ({After} 10. Nc3 {Black has} b5 $1 {,exploiting the fact that upon} 11. axb5 $4 ({White would have to settle for} 11. Qd3 b4 12. Nb1 Be4 {, when he is pushed backwards without causing anydamage to Black's pawn structure}) ({or similarly} 11. Qa2 b4) ({or} 11. Qb3 b4) 11... axb5 {, White can resign as both his rook on a1 and queen are hanging.--- I recall Lev Polugaevsky falling for this trap versus Braga in Mar delPlata 1982. He lamented in Grandmaster Preparation, "Suddenly I mechanicallypicked up the wrong piece. The saddest thing is that I not only knew all theconsequences of this incorrect move, but had even pointed them out myself inthe notes to one of my games." Polugaevsky was more sanguine than you mightexpect, because he somehow turned the game around and won (with some help fromhis opponent, it must be admitted.).}) 10... Bd5 {Black prepares his freeingmove ...c7-c5 with gain of time by hitting the white queen.} ({If} 10... Nbd711. Nc3 h6 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 {, White can play} 13. Rfe1 {, looking to expand inthe centre with 14 e4;} ({or else gain space on the queenside with} 13. b4 {:for example,} Bd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Qb3 Bd6 16. e3 {planning an eventual b4-b5minority attack.})) ({Alternatively,} 10... a5 {clears the a6-square for theblack knight (or rook!) and fixes the pawns on the queenside, preventing Whitegaining space with b2-b4. After} 11. b4 Na6 ({the strange-looking} 11... Ra6 {has been used a couple of times by Aronian, with the idea of ...Rb6 to attackthe b2-pawn}) 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. e4 Nxb4 14. Rd1 {, White has built a centre,but Black has the two bishops.}) 11. Qc2 Be4 {Driving the queen back evenfurther.} 12. Qd1 ({Instead,} 12. Qc1 {deters the ...c7-c5 advance (thoughNakamura in the main game and Leko in the notes to 14 Qxd8 seem to welcomethis move!). For example,} h6 ({a solid alternative for Black is} 12... Nc6 13.e3 Nb4 14. Nc3 Bc6 {, though White has a small plus}) 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Rd1 a515. Nbd2 Bh7 $6 {(the bishop ends up out of things on h7)} ({it was better toplay} 15... Bxf3 16. Bxf3 c6 {to fortify the centre, though} 17. Nc4 {is someedge for White}) 16. Nb3 c6 17. Qc3 Be7 18. Nc5 Qc7 19. Ne5 Na6 20. Nxb7 $1 {(a strong breakthrough)} Qxb7 21. Bxc6 Qc7 ({a better defence was} 21... Qb8 $122. Bxa8 Bb4 23. Qc6 Qxa8 24. f3 {, though White has the superior chancesbecause he has a rook and two pawns for two pieces, and White is never matedin the Catalan!}) 22. Bxa8 Qxc3 23. bxc3 Rxa8 24. Nc6 $1 {and White went in towin in P.Eljanov-H.Nakamura, Baku 2015.}) 12... c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Qxd8 ({Back in the 1980s such play would indicate the likelihood of a 20-move draw,but nowadays top players believe in the tiniest of advantages. Here is anotherexample:} 14. Nbd2 Bc6 15. Ne5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Be7 17. Rc1 Nbd7 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 19.Nf3 Qxd1 20. Rfxd1 Rfc8 21. Ne5 {and White ground out a win in thisequal-looking position in A.Giri-P.Leko, Baku 2015.}) 14... Rxd8 {Black hasliquidated White's pawn centre without incurring any obvious weaknesses in hisown pawn structure. His pieces are on active squares and he has brought his'problem' bishop to c6 to contest control of the long diagonal. --- It feelslike Black has solved most of his problems and yet Anand, a world champion atmany time controls, won't be able to hold Black's position against Nakamura'sprobing. Such is the difficulty of defending very slightly worse positions inthe Catalan endgame. --- QUESTION: Should White continue with 15 Nbd2 or 15Nc3 to develop his queenside?} 15. Nbd2 ({ANSWER: After} 15. Nc3 Bc6 {, thewhite knight on c3 doesn't have much to do, whereas from d2 it can leap to b3and a5 if allowed to put pressure on Black's queenside.}) 15... Bc6 16. Nb3 Be7{Breaking the pin on f6.} ({Instead,} 16... Bb6 {prevents White's next move,but Black hasn't shaken off White's slight edge after} 17. Ne5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2Nbd7 19. Nd3 Rac8 20. Rfc1 {, etc.}) 17. Na5 h6 18. Be3 ({If} 18. Bd2 $2 {heloses a piece to} Bxf3 {, so first of all the bishop goes to e3.}) 18... Nd519. Bd2 Nb6 20. Bf4 {White's bishop plays cat and mouse with the black knight.}Nd5 21. Ne5 {At last the bishop stops running.} g5 {One more kick at thecleric.} ({After} 21... Nxf4 22. gxf4 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 Nd7 24. Nd3 Rab8 25. Rfc1Bd6 26. Rc3 {, White can still keep on prodding the black queenside, hopinghis opponent loses patience and weakens himself.}) 22. Bd2 Bf6 23. Nd3 ({EXERCISE: How would you assess the position after} 23. Nexc6 Nxc6 24. Nxc6 bxc6{- ? --- ANSWER: White would gain the bishop pair and leave Black with brokenqueenside pawns. On the other hand, Black's knight is well placed on d5 andWhite has a weakling of his own on b2. Nonetheless, after} 25. Rab1 {intending26 Rfc1 White looks on top. Perhaps Nakamura didn't like the variation} Be7 26.Rfc1 Nb4 27. Bxb4 ({here} 27. Be1 $5 {intending 28 Rc4 might offer more chances}) 27... Bxb4 28. Rxc6 a5 {, when with the black bishop stopping b2-b4 foreverit is very unlikely White could win.}) 23... b6 24. Nc4 {White's knights aregoing backwards and forwards, not landing any strong blow, but not allowingAnand to kill off the game either and forcing him to be vigilant.} b5 25. Bxd5bxc4 ({I guess} 25... Rxd5 {is the worst of the four recaptures, losing theexchange to} 26. Nb6 {;}) ({while not far behind is} 25... Bxd5 26. Nb6 Ra7 27.axb5 {, losing a pawn;}) ({but we should take} 25... exd5 {seriously. It lookswrong at first glance, but it has the good point that it virtually forcesWhite to activate the black knight on b8 in the sequence} 26. Nce5 bxa4 27.Nxc6 Nxc6 28. Rxa4 Nd4 {and Black has counterplay. --- Anand saw he was okayafter the game move and so probably didn't think much about alternatives.}) 26.Bxc4 Bxb2 {The idea is that Black gets his piece back after 27 Nxb2 Rxd2 witheven chances. Nakamura finds a way to keep the tension.} 27. Ra2 Bg7 ({A moreactive retreat was} 27... Bd4 {which would prevent White's 29th move.}) 28. Rc1Be8 29. Nc5 Bf8 {EXERCISE: What is the best way to meet the threat to c5? ---ANSWER:} 30. Bd3 $1 {White defends his own knight and regroups his bishop toe4, where it will ha