e passive oneon b8 to the open file. He might also have thought the rook on f8 was doing agood job defending f7 and in fact he probably assumed that White wouldexchange on e8 whichever rook he put there, so it didn't matter much...} ({ANSWER: Black should use the other rook with} 25... Rfe8 $1 {. After} 26. Rxe8+({alternatively, if} 26. Rf1 {then} Re6 $1 27. Rxd6 Rxd6 28. Qxd6 Rc8 {isequal - now it is Black who has the active rook to offset his slightly worsepawn structure}) 26... Rxe8 27. Rxb7 {, then} Re6 $1 {breaks the attack on f6and keeps the rook active. White has no advantage in view of Black's threat ofcounterplay with, say, ...Qd3 intending ...Re1+. --- You might wonder why Ipraised 25 Rb6 when Black can equalize against it. Well, Aronian isworld-class player and it made him go wrong! That is quite good enough in theCatalan. You have to keep pressing, not releasing the tension, and trust thatyour opponent will play over passively or inaccurately.}) 26. Rf1 $1 {Afterthis quiet move Black is left with a hanging pawn on b7 and an inactive rookon f8.} Qe4 $2 {His inaccuracy on the previous move seems to have flusteredAronian.} ({Instead,} 26... Re7 27. Rxd6 Rfe8 {leaves him with active rooksand not much to fear, despite his worse pawn structure.}) 27. Qxb7 Qxb7 ({After} 27... Qxd4 28. Rxa6 {the passed a-pawn is a nuisance for Black to defendagainst.}) 28. Rxb7 Re4 29. Rd1 Rc8 30. Rb6 $2 {White's winning chances dependon undermining Black's kingside pawns whilst at the same time ensuring that f2is adequately defended if Black's rooks are doubled against it. This can beachieved by bringing the rook on d1 into an attack on f7.} ({Therefore} 30. Ra7$1 {was the correct approach: for example,} Rc2 31. Rb1 $1 {That means} Ra2 {is the last try for Black, but he ends up under intense pressure after} ({andnow Black's doubling of rooks on the seventh rank fails after} 31... Ree2 32.Rb8+ Kh7 33. Rxf7 {, etc. White's king remains secure whilst the 