n on a post where she supports the e2-e4 advance.}) 9... Bc6 ({After} 9... Nc6 10. Qxc4 {while there is a tricky line with} b5 {, but White emergeswith a small edge after} ({White has lasting pressure upon} 10... Nb4 11. Nc3Bc6 12. a5 {;} (12. --)) 11. axb5 axb5 12. Rxa8 Qxa8 13. Qxb5 Qa1 ({not} 13...Nxd4 $2 14. Nxd4 Bxb5 15. Bxa8 {when White wins a piece}) 14. Nc3 Nxd4 15. Qb7{.}) ({Meanwhile} 9... c5 {looks risky for Black as his queen is pinned. Playcould go} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 ({if} 10... Nc6 11. Qxc4) 11. Ne5 Qc8 12. Qxc4 Bb5 {(aflashy move based on 13 axb5? axb5, when White has a rook on a1 and queen bothhanging)} 13. Qb3 Bc6 ({if} 13... Bxe2 14. Re1 {when e2 and b7 are attacked})14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. Na3 {with White enjoying the better game thanks to thebishop pair.}) 10. Nc3 {This is a very dangerous line for Black to face.Routine developing moves will quickly lead to disaster.} Nbd7 $2 {Just whatWhite was hoping for. Black innocently brings out his knight, not realizingthat a cataclysm is going to hit his centre.} ({If instead he tries to exploitthe hole on b4 by inserting a knight on d3 he is driven back:} 10... Nd5 11. e4Nb4 12. Qe2 Nd3 13. Be3 Bb4 14. Ne1 {(the simplest riposte)} Nxe1 15. Rxe1 a516. Qxc4 {with the better game for White due to his excellent centre, thoughBlack can resist with} Qe7 {.}) ({A better approach for Black is to exchangeoff his loose bishop at once with} 10... Bxf3 {, as we shall see in the nextgame.}) 11. e4 b5 {EXERCISE: If you were playing White how would you handlethe breakthrough in the centre? What would be your next two moves? --- ANSWER:}12. d5 $1 exd5 13. e5 $1 {It isn't always right to recapture.} ({After} 13.exd5 Bb7 {, the centre remains stable: White's advance has stalled. The rookon d1 and the bishop on g2 would be angry at having their view of the boardobstructed by their own pawn on d5. In contrast, after the game move the blackknight is driven from f6, the black pawn on d5 falls to the white knight, andWhite's rook on d1 and bishop on g2 are happy with their lives again.}) 13...Ne4 ({Black could try to make the best of it with a piece sacrifice for a fewpawns, but he is unable to hold his centre together after} 13... Nc5 14. Nd4Bb7 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxa8 Bxa8 {because of} 18. Nxd5 $1 Bxd5 19.Nc6 {when either his queen or d5 falls off the board.}) 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Rxd5Nec5 16. axb5 axb5 {EXERCISE: Can you see a winning combination for White?} ({Former world champion Anatoly Karpov once stumbled into this position as Black,though to be fair it was in a blindfold game. His intuition or calculationallowed him to avoid the worst with} 16... Qe8 {, although} 17. Ng5 $1 {stillleaves Black in desperate trouble;} ({instead of the} 17. bxa6 $2 {of J.Piket-A.Karpov, Monaco (blindfold) 1996.})) 17. Rxa8 {ANSWER!} Qxa8 18. Rxd7 $1{Setting up a discovered attack on the black queen.} Nxd7 19. Ng5 {A hyped-upversion of a familiar tactical motif in the Catalan and Queen's Indian set-ups.Normally it's a black rook that's the victim on a8, but here it's the queen.}g6 {There's no way to stop mate on h7 and save the queen.} 20. Bxa8 1-0[Event "38: Belgian League"][Site "?"][Date "2014.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Khenkin, I."][Black "Rozentalis, E."][Result "1/2-1/2"][ECO "E06"][Annotator "Neil McDonald"][PlyCount "71"][EventDate "2014.??.??"][SourceTitle "The Catalan MBM"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2017.08.07"]1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4Bd7 9. Rd1 Bc6 10. Nc3 Bxf3 {Black exchanges off the bishop before 11 e4leaves him facing the d4-d5 advance that proved so powerful in the previousgame. At the same time the c6-square is cleared for the black knight.} 11. Bxf3Nc6 ({After the passive} 11... c6 {, White could clear the way for his queento capture the c4-pawn whilst restricting Black's queenside with} 12. a5 $1 {: for example,} Nd5 ({or} 12... Nbd7 13. Qa4 {and 14 Qxc4}) 13