e fork on d5 withoutgiving himself more weaknesses with} 24... c6 $2) 25. axb5 Ra8 26. Na4 Rxb5 27.Rxc7 {when Black is still somewhat boxed in, but after} Be7 {should hold thedraw}) 20. Rc2 Rfb8 21. Nc1 {(for the moment the black rooks are stopped fromtaking on b2 thanks to some dainty footwork by the knight; this will giveBarnusz the time to utilize his kingside pawn majority)} e5 22. dxe5 Bxe5 23.Nd3 Bd6 24. e4 $1 {(in the absence of the black rooks White will be able tocreate direct threats against the underdefended black king)} Rb3 25. Rd2 g6 26.Rbd1 Qg4 27. Qxc6 h5 28. e5 Bf8 29. Nf4 $1 {(at last the b2-pawn can bejettisoned in favour of building up the kingside attack)} Rxb2 30. h3 Qf5 31.Rxb2 Rxb2 32. h4 Rb1 33. Rxb1 Qxb1+ 34. Kg2 Qb6 35. Qa8 {(the perfect squarefor the queen from where she attacks a5 and is ready to switch to the kingside)} Qb4 36. e6 $1 {(the white queen and knight are a potent attacking forceagainst the black king)} Kg7 37. exf7 Kxf7 38. Qd5+ Ke8 {(Black's defencescrumble)} ({as shown too by} 38... Kg7 39. Qe5+ Kh7 40. Qe6 Qb1 41. Qf7+ Bg742. Ne6 Qb2 43. Ng5+ Kh6 44. Qg8 {with the deadly threat of mate on h7}) 39.Nxg6 Bd6 40. Qe6+ Kd8 41. Nh8 $1 {(a knight on the rim is dim? - here thethreat of mate on f7 allows the knight to get to the dominant e5-square withgain of time)} Be7 42. Nf7+ Ke8 43. Ne5 Qd6 44. Qf7+ {1-0. After} Kd8 45. Qg8+{Black loses his queen to a fork.}) 13... Rb8 {The best defensive move. Blackprepares to challenge the white rook before it can begin chomping through theblack pawns with Ra4 and Rxc4, when c6 would soon drop.} 14. Ra4 Rb4 15. Na2 $1({Carefully does it - after} 15. Rxb4 Bxb4 {the a5-pawn would hang, so Whiteforces the black rook into making the exchange.}) 15... Rxa4 16. Qxa4 Qb8 17.Qxc4 ({Awkward for White is} 17. Qxc6 $2 Qb3 18. Nc3 Bb4 {, when Blackthreatens to win a piece.}) 17... Qb7 {Rozentalis has managed to secure hisflimsy queenside structure, albeit at the cost of the c4-p