te wins the exchange.}) 17. Qe2 Qb6 18. Nc5 Bxc519. Rxc5 {Black is far from lost, but the opening has clearly been a successfor White. He has restrained Black from breaking out with ...c7-c5 and candouble his rooks against c7. Abdyjapar disagrees with this verdict and soongets into hot water.} Nd7 20. Rc3 $2 ({The undefended bishop motif strikesagain in a more sophisticated form after} 20. Ng5 $1 {.} {That leaves only} Bg6{, but then White's pressure along the c-file is supercharged with} ({Thenacceptance of the material with} 20... Bxg2 21. Qh5 $1 {is fatal for Black:for example,} Bc6 22. Qxh7+ Kf8 23. Qh5 $1 {and there is no good way to defendf7 for if} g6 24. Qh7 {and the white queen crashes in.} (24. --)) ({If instead} 20... Nxc5 21. dxc5 Qxc5 22. Nxe4 {and White's minor pieces are worth muchmore than the rook and pawn.}) 21. Rc6 Qb8 22. Rac1 {.}) 20... c5 $2 {Blackmakes another positionally desirable move that is tactically unsound. Ifcarried on too long this approach is bound to lead to disaster, if not in onegame then in the next one. As the renowned strategist Reti affirmed thefoundation of positional play is control of tactics.} 21. Rac1 ({The} 21. Ng5$1 {recipe still works:} Bxg2 22. Qh5 Qc6 23. Qxh7+ Kf8 24. Qh5 $1 g6 25. Qh7 {and the black king will be eviscerated. The game move isn't so strong, butgives White a good game because of the awkward pin on the c5-pawn.}) 21... h6$2 ({If Black had tried} 21... c4 {instead, then} 22. b3 {would win thec4-pawn, but} Qd6 $1 {counterattacking against a3 helps Black resist strongly.}) ({Meanwhile,} 21... Bb7 22. Ng5 $1 Bxg2 23. Qh5 $1 {gives White a decisiveattack of the kind discussed above at his 20th and 21st moves.}) 22. Ne5 $1 {Winning the c5-pawn with a simple combination.} Bxg2 23. Nxd7 Qb7 {Black'sattempt to gain counterplay by sacrificing the exchange is doomed if Whiteplays steadily.} ({However, the alternative} 23... Qd6 24. Kxg2 Qxd7 25. Rxc5 {is a slow but sure defeat.}) 24. Nx