s underirritating pressure.} ({After the immediate} 11. Nbd2 {, the} c5 {stab alreadyequalizes:} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. dxc5 Rc8 14. Nb3 Bd5 15. Rfd1 Qe7 16. e4 Bxb3 17.axb3 Rxc5 {, etc. Therefore White deflects the black knight from d7 so that itno longer supports the ...c7-c5 thrust.}) 11... Nxf6 ({After} 11... Bxf6 $2 12.Ng5 $1 {(threatening mate)} Bxg5 13. Bxb7 {is an unfortunate swap for Black ashe is left with light-squared holes on the queenside. Always watch out for theNg5 trap!}) 12. Nbd2 {An arms race: White wants to get his knight to b3 beforeBlack can arrange 12...Rc8 and 13...c5.} Rc8 13. Nb3 {Just in time to stop ...c7-c5 - maybe not!} Be4 {Black still hopes to drive the white queen from thec-file in order to facilitate the freeing move ...c7-c5. For this purpose heutilizes the e4-square which is left undefended after White's last move, andalso the d5-square with his knight.} ({EXERCISE: What happens after 13...c5now? --- ANSWER:} 13... c5 $5 {looks possible, with Black being okay at theend of this sharp clash:} 14. dxc5 ({not} 14. Nxc5 $2 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Qxd4 16.Nb3 {and now the desperado} Qxf2+ $1 {followed by 17..Rxc2 wins a pawn forBlack}) 14... Be4 15. Qc3 Bd5 16. Rfd1 ({White has nothing after} 16. Rac1 Bxb317. Qxb3 Bxc5 18. e3 {anti xf2} Qb6 19. Rc2 {equal}) 16... Ne4 17. Qe1 Bxc5 18.Nxc5 Rxc5 19. Ne5 f5 20. f3 Nd6 21. e4 fxe4 22. fxe4 Bb7 23. Qb4 Rxe5 24. Rxd6Qc7 25. Rad1 Bc8 {with equal chances.}) 14. Qc3 Nd5 ({Notice that with d4defended by the white queen,} 14... c5 $2 {now just drops a pawn to} 15. Nxc5 {.}) ({Alternatively,} 14... Qd5 15. Rfc1 Rfd8 16. Qa5 Qb7 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. Rxc5Nd7 19. Rcc1 {looks slightly better for White.}) 15. Qc6 {The c6-square lookslike a risky place for the white pieces to have a picnic, but both the queenand a rook will utilize it over the coming moves. The stakes are high. Blackcan unleash a dangerous discovered attack from the bishop on e4 (once it isguarded of course), but if this fails to gi